\u699c__\u4e2d\u56fd\u4f01\u4e1a\u5bb6\u7f51|website=www.iceo.com.cn|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\nFortune -40 Under 40 (Global)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/40-under-40/|title=40 Under 40: The Most Influential Young People in Business 2018|date=2018-07-19|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-08-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nFortune -40 Under 40 (China)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortunechina.com/rankings/c/2015-11/02/content_248895.htm|title=2015\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd40\u4f4d40\u5c81\u4ee5\u4e0b\u7684\u5546\u754c\u7cbe\u82f1 - \u8d22\u5bcc\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51|website=www.fortunechina.com|access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n'''2013'''\n\nChina Entrepreneurs Magazine-China's Top Women Business Leaders\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.xiaojukeji.com/news/newslisten Corporate Website of Didi Chuxing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Qing}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Beijing]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Peking University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chinese women business executives]]\n[[Category:Chinese chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Goldman Sachs people]]\n[[Category:DiDi people]]\n", "name_user": "Jiao reddy", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liu_Qing_(businesswoman)"}
{"title_page": "Sh\u014djo manga", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Sh\u014djo'' manga}}\n{{short description|Manga aimed at a teenage female readership}}\n{{other uses of|sh\u014djo|Shojo (disambiguation)}}\n{{Anime and manga}}\n[[File:Shoujo November 1910 with translation.jpg|thumb|200px|A simple four-panel manga from the November 1910 issue of ''Sh\u014djo'' magazine (artist unknown)]]\n[[File:Nazo no clover page 7.jpg|thumb|200px|A page from [[Katsuji Matsumoto]]'s groundbreaking 1934 ''sh\u014djo'' manga series, ''The Mysterious Clover'']]\n'''Shojo''', {{nihongo|'''''shoujo''''', or '''''sh\u014djo'' manga'''|\u5c11\u5973\u6f2b\u753b}} is [[manga]] aimed at a young teen female [[Target audience|target]]-[[Demography|demographic]] readership. The name [[Romanization of Japanese|romanizes]] the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] '''[[wikt:\u5c11\u5973|\u5c11\u5973]]''' ([[wikt:sh\u014djo|''sh\u014djo'']]), literally \"young woman\". ''Sh\u014djo'' manga covers many subjects in a variety of narrative styles, from [[Period piece|historical drama]] to [[science fiction]], often with a focus on romantic relationships or emotions.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\">{{cite magazine |editor1-last=Toku |editor1-first=Masami |date=2005 |title=Shojo Manga: Girl Power! |url=http://www.csuchico.edu/pub/cs/spring_06/feature_03.html |url-status=dead |magazine=Chico Statements Magazine |publisher=[[California State University, Chico]] |isbn=1-886226-10-5 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010233300/http://www.csuchico.edu/pub/cs/spring_06/feature_03.html |archive-date=October 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, however, ''sh\u014djo'' manga does not comprise a style or genre, but rather indicates a [[Target audience|target demographic]].<ref name=\"Thorn 2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219032133/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/japan_quarterly/index.html |archivedate=February 19, 2007 |url-status=dead |journal=The Japan Quarterly |url=http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/japan_quarterly/index.html |title=Sh\u00f4jo Manga\u2014Something for the Girls |volume=48 |issue=3 |publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |location=Tokyo, Japan |date=2001}}</ref><ref name=\"Thorn 2004\">{{cite web |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=What Sh\u00f4jo Manga Are and Are Not: A Quick Guide for the Confused |url=http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/whatisandisnt.php |website=Matt-Thorn.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118080220/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/whatisandisnt.php |archivedate=November 18, 2015 |date=2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nJapanese magazines specifically for girls, known as ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' magazines, first appeared in 1902 with the founding of {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u754c|Sh\u014djo-kai|lit. \"Girls' World\"}} and continued with others such as {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u4e16\u754c|[[Sh\u014djo Sekai]]|lit. \"Girls' World\"}} (1906) and the long-running {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u306e\u53cb|Sh\u014djo no Tomo|lit. \"Girls' Friend\"}} (1908).<ref name=\"Thorn 2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:\u660e\u6cbb\uff5e\u662d\u548c \u5c11\u5973\u96d1\u8a8c\u306e\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb |trans-title=Meiji \u2013 Sh\u014dwa: An Introduction to Girls' Magazines |url=https://www.kikuyo-lib.jp/?page_id=119 |website=Kikuy\u014d Town Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104000351/https://www.kikuyo-lib.jp/?page_id=119 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |location=[[Kikuy\u014d, Kumamoto|Kikuy\u014d, Kumamoto, Japan]] |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe roots of the wide-eyed look commonly associated with ''sh\u014djo'' manga date back to ''sh\u014djo'' magazine illustrations during the early 20th century. The most important illustrators associated with this style at the time were [[Yumeji Takehisa]] and particularly [[Jun'ichi Nakahara]], who, influenced by his work as a doll creator, frequently drew female characters with big eyes in the early 20th century. This had a significant influence on early ''sh\u014djo'' manga, evident in the work of influential [[manga artist]]s such as {{ill|Macoto Takahashi (illustrator)|ja|\u9ad8\u6a4b\u771f\u7434|lt=Macoto Takahashi}} and [[Riyoko Ikeda]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j1LLCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=International Perspectives on Shojo and Shojo Manga: The Influence of Girl Culture |editor1-last=Toku |editor1-first=Masami |page=24 |last1=Masuda |first1=Nozomi |chapter=Shojo Manga and Its Acceptance |date=June 5, 2015 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-1-138-80948-2 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nSimple, single-page manga began to appear in these magazines by 1910, and by the 1930s more sophisticated humor-strips had become an essential feature of most girls' magazines. The most popular manga, [[Katsuji Matsumoto]]'s {{Nihongo3||\u304f\u308b\u304f\u308b\u30af\u30eb\u30df\u3061\u3083\u3093|Kurukuru Kurumi-chan}}, debuted on the pages of ''Sh\u014djo no Tomo'' in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=Pre-World War II Sh\u00f4jo Manga and Illustrations |url=http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/prewar_shoujo/index.php |website=Matt-Thorn.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304214610/http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/prewar_shoujo/index.php |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> As [[World War II]] progressed, however, \"comics, perhaps regarded as frivolous, began to disappear\".<ref name=\"Schodt 1983\">{{cite book |last1=Schodt |first1=Frederik L. |authorlink1=Frederik L. Schodt |title=Manga! Manga! The World of Japanese Comics |date=January 25, 2013 |orig-year=First published in 1983 |publisher=[[Kodansha USA]] |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-56836-476-6|title-link=Manga! Manga! The World of Japanese Comics }}</ref>\n\nPostwar ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as [[Shosuke Kurakane]]'s popular {{Nihongo3||\u3042\u3093\u307f\u3064\u59eb|[[Anmitsu Hime]]|lit. \"Princess Anmitsu\"}},<ref>[[Yoshihiro Yonezawa|Yonezawa, Yoshihiro]], ed. (1991). {{Nihongo3|\"A Children's History of Showa-Era Japan: The World of Sh\u014djo Manga I, 1945\u20131962\"|\u5b50\u4f9b\u306e\u662d\u548c\u53f2\u2500\u2500\u5c11\u5973\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u306e\u4e16\u754c I \u662d\u548c20\u5e74\u301c37\u5e74|Kodomo no Sh\u014dwa-shi: Sh\u014djo manga no sekai I, Sh\u014dwa 20 nen \u2013 37 nen}}. Bessatsu Taiy\u014d series. Tokyo, Japan: Heibonsha. {{ISBN|978-4-582-94239-2}}.</ref> initially followed the pre-war pattern of simple humor-strips. But [[Osamu Tezuka]]'s postwar revolution, introducing intense drama and serious themes to children's manga, spread quickly to ''sh\u014djo'' manga, particularly after the enormous success of his seminal {{Nihongo|''[[Princess Knight]]''|\u30ea\u30dc\u30f3\u306e\u9a0e\u58eb|Ribon no Kishi}}.<ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/>\n\nUntil the mid-1960s, men vastly outnumbered the women (for example: [[Toshiko Ueda]], [[Hideko Mizuno]], [[Masako Watanabe]], and [[Miyako Maki]]) among the artists working on ''sh\u014djo'' manga. Many male manga artists, such as [[Tetsuya Chiba]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=The Moto Hagio Interview |publisher=[[Fantagraphics Books]] |journal=[[The Comics Journal]] |issue=269 |date=2005 |location=Seattle, WA |url=http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/hagio_interview.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113194502/http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/hagio_interview.php |archivedate=January 13, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> functioned as rookies, waiting for an opportunity to move over to [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' (\u5c11\u5e74 \"boys'\") manga]]. Chiba asked his wife about girls' feelings for research for his manga. At this time, conventional job opportunities for Japanese women did not include becoming a manga artist.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Toku |first1=Masami |title=Shojo Manga! Girls' Comics! A Mirror of Girls' Dreams |journal=[[Mechademia]] |date=2007 |volume=2 |pages=22\u201323 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=Minneapolis, MN |url=http://www.upress.umn.edu/Books/L/lunning_mechademia2.html |issn=19342489}}</ref> Adapting Tezuka's dynamic style to ''sh\u014djo'' manga (which had always been domestic in nature) proved challenging. According to [[Rachel Matt Thorn|Rachel Thorn]]:\n\n<blockquote>While some chose to simply create longer humor-strips, others turned to popular girls' novels of the day as a model for melodramatic ''sh\u014djo'' manga. These manga featured sweet, innocent pre-teen heroines, torn from the safety of family and tossed from one perilous circumstance to another, until finally rescued (usually by a kind, handsome young man) and re-united with their families.<ref>[[Rachel Matt Thorn|Thorn, Rachel Matt]] (March 15, 2008). \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160108135716/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/colloque/index.php The Multi-Faceted Universe of Sh\u014djo Manga]\". Presented at ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090902061831/http://www.mcjp.asso.fr/pjanv2008/conferences/manga/index.html Le manga, 60 ans apr\u00e8s...]''. Paris, France. Archived from [http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/colloque/index.php the original] on January 8, 2016.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThese early ''sh\u014djo'' manga almost invariably had pre-adolescent girls as both heroines and readers. Unless they used a fantastic setting (as in ''Princess Knight'') or a backdrop of a distant time or place, romantic love for the heroine remained essentially taboo. But the average age of the readership rose, and its interests changed. In the mid-1960s one of the few female artists in the field, [[Yoshiko Nishitani]], began to draw stories featuring contemporary Japanese teenagers in love. This signaled a dramatic transformation of the genre.<ref name=\"Yonezawa 1991\">[[Yoshihiro Yonezawa|Yonezawa, Yoshihiro]], ed. (1991). {{Nihongo3|\"A Children's History of Showa-Era Japan: The World of Sh\u014djo Manga II, 1963\u20131989\"|\u5b50\u4f9b\u306e\u662d\u548c\u53f2\u2500\u2500\u5c11\u5973\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u306e\u4e16\u754c II \u662d\u548c38\u5e74\u301c64\u5e74|Kodomo no Sh\u014dwa-shi: Sh\u014djo manga no sekai II, Sh\u014dwa 38 nen \u2013 64 nen}}. Bessatsu Taiy\u014d series. Tokyo, Japan: Heibonsha. {{ISBN|978-4-582-94240-8}}.</ref><ref name=\"Thorn 2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=The Magnificent Forty-Niners |issue=269 |date=2005 |journal=[[The Comics Journal]] |publisher=[[Fantagraphics Books]] |location=Seattle, WA |url=https://www.en.matt-thorn.com/single-post/2017/05/31/The-Magnificent-Forty-Niners |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102223859/https://www.en.matt-thorn.com/single-post/2017/05/31/The-Magnificent-Forty-Niners |archivedate=November 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This may have been due to the [[baby boomers]] becoming teens, and the industry trying to keep them as readers.<ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/>\n\nBetween 1950 and 1969, increasingly large audiences for manga emerged in Japan with the solidification of its two main marketing genres, [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] aimed at adolescent boys and ''sh\u014djo'' manga aimed at adolescent girls.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\"/><ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/> These romantic comedy ''sh\u014djo'' manga were inspired by American TV dramas of the time.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saito |first1=Kumiko |title=Desire in Subtext: Gender, Fandom, and Women's Male-Male Homoerotic Parodies in Contemporary Japan |journal=[[Mechademia]] |volume=6 |page=173 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=Minneapolis, MN |url=https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/mechademia-6 |issn=1934-2489 |date=2011}}</ref> The success of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, and the gold medal won by the [[Japan women's national volleyball team]], influenced a series of sports ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as {{Nihongo|''[[Attack No. 1]]''|\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30afNo.1|Atakku Nanb\u0101 Wan}}. On December 5, 1966, the first ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' [[anime]] series, {{Nihongo|''[[Sally the Witch]]''|\u9b54\u6cd5\u4f7f\u3044\u30b5\u30ea\u30fc|Mah\u014dtsukai Sar\u012b}}, premiered in Japan on [[TV Asahi|NET TV]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Witches in Anime |url=http://www.mindspring.com/~theduffields/resume/articles/features/witches.htm |newspaper=[[Animerica Extra]] |volume=3 |issue=11 |date=October 2000 |last1=Duffield |first1=Patricia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103230229/http://www.mindspring.com/~theduffields/resume/articles/features/witches.htm |archive-date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 1967, ''sh\u014djo'' manga began being published in ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' format.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=K\u00e1lovics |first1=Dalma |url=http://www.kyoto-seika.ac.jp/researchlab/wp/wp-content/uploads/sa_dalma_kalovics1.pdf |title=The missing link of sh\u014djo manga history: the changes in 60s sh\u014djo manga as seen through the magazine ''Sh\u016bkan Margaret'' |journal=Ky\u014dto Seika Daigaku Kiy\u014d |issue=49 |publisher=[[Kyoto Seika University]] |date=2016 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104101525/http://www.kyoto-seika.ac.jp/researchlab/wp/wp-content/uploads/sa_dalma_kalovics1.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween roughly 1969 and 1971, a flood of young female manga artists transformed the genre again. Some, including [[Moto Hagio]], [[Yumiko \u014cshima]], and [[Keiko Takemiya]], became known as the {{Nihongo|[[Year 24 Group]]|24\u5e74\u7d44|Nij\u016byo-nen Gumi}}, or the {{Nihongo|Fabulous Year 24 Group|\u82b1\u306e24\u5e74\u7d44|Hana no Nij\u016byo-nen Gumi}}, so named from the approximate year of birth many of them shared: [[Sh\u014dwa period|Sh\u014dwa]] 24, or 1949. This loosely defined group experimented with content and form, inventing such subgenres such as ''[[sh\u014dnen-ai]]'' (boys' love), and earning the long-maligned ''sh\u014djo'' manga unprecedented critical praise.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Contemporary Japanese Women's Theatre and Visual Arts|last=Anan|first=Nobuko|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=9781349557066|location=London|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137372987}}</ref> Other female artists of the same generation, such as [[Riyoko Ikeda]], [[Yukari Ichijo]], and [[Sumika Yamamoto]], garnered unprecedented popular support with such hits (respectively) as {{Nihongo|''[[The Rose of Versailles]]''|\u30d9\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30e6\u306e\u3070\u3089|Berusaiyu no Bara}}, {{Nihongo3||\u30c7\u30b6\u30a4\u30ca\u30fc|Dezainaa|lit. \"Designer\"}}, and {{Nihongo|''[[Aim for the Ace!]]''|\u30a8\u30fc\u30b9\u3092\u306d\u3089\u3048!|\u0112su o Nerae!}}.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\"/><ref name=\"Thorn 2001\"/><ref name=\"Yonezawa 1991\"/><ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/><ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/><ref name=\"Manga Sixty Years 1\">{{cite book |last1=Gravett |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Gravett |title=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics |date=July 19, 2004 |publisher=Harper Design |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-85669-391-2 |pages=78\u201380|title-link=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics }}</ref><ref>Lent, 2001, ''op. cit.'', pp. 9\u201310.</ref>{{Volume needed|date=January 2010}} During that era, women's roles in Japanese society were changing, and women were being elected to the [[National Diet]], and publishers responded by employing more female talent.<ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/>  Since the mid-1970s, women have created the vast majority of ''sh\u014djo'' manga; notable exceptions include [[Patariro|Mineo Maya]] and [[Shinji Wada]].\n\nFrom 1975, ''sh\u014djo'' manga continued to develop stylistically while simultaneously branching out into different but overlapping subgenres.<ref name=\"\u014cgi\">{{cite journal |last1=\u014cgi |first1=Fusami |url=http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/content/BPL_images/Journal_Samples2/JPCU0022-3840~36~4/045.PDF |title=Female Subjectivity and ''Shoujo'' (Girls) ''Manga'' (Japanese Comics): ''Shoujo'' in Ladies' Comics and Young Ladies' Comics |journal=[[The Journal of Popular Culture]] |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell|Blackwell Publishing]] |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=780\u2013803 |date=2003 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104101314/http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/content/BPL_images/Journal_Samples2/JPCU0022-3840~36~4/045.PDF |url-status=live|doi=10.1111/1540-5931.00045 }}</ref> [[Meiji University]] professor [[Yukari Fujimoto]] writes that during the 1990s, ''sh\u014djo'' manga became concerned with self-fulfillment. She intimates that the 1990\u20131991 [[Gulf War]] influenced the development of female characters \"who fight to protect the destiny of a community\", such as ''[[Red River (manga)|Red River]]'', ''[[Basara (manga)|Basara]]'', ''[[Magic Knight Rayearth]]'', and ''[[Sailor Moon]]''. Fujimoto opines that the ''sh\u014djo'' manga of the 1990s depicted emotional bonds between women as stronger than the bonds between a man and a woman.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Fujimoto |first1=Yukari |authorlink1=Yukari Fujimoto |date=2008 |title=Japanese Contemporary Manga (Number 1): ''Sh\u014djo'' (Girls Manga) |url=http://www.jpf.go.jp/JF_Contents/GetImage/img_pdf/JBN56.pdf?ContentNo=9&SubsystemNo=1&FileName=img_pdf/JBN56.pdf |language= |magazine=Japanese Book News |volume=56 |page=12 |publisher=[[Japan Foundation|The Japan Foundation]] |accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Major subgenres include romance, science fiction, fantasy, [[magical girls]], ''[[yaoi]]'', and \"[[Josei manga|ladies comics]]\" (in Japanese, ''redisu'' \u30ec\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30b9, ''redikomi'' \u30ec\u30c7\u30a3\u30b3\u30df, and ''josei'' \u5973\u6027).<ref name=\"Manga Sixty Years 2\">{{cite book |last1=Gravett |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Gravett |title=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics |date=July 19, 2004 |publisher=Harper Design |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-85669-391-2 |page=8|title-link=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics }}</ref><ref name=\"Schodt 1996\">{{cite book |last1=Schodt |first1=Frederik L. |authorlink1=Frederik L. Schodt |title=Dreamland Japan: Writings on Modern Manga |date=1996 |publisher=Stone Bridge Press |location=Berkeley, CA |isbn=978-1-880656-23-5|title-link=Dreamland Japan }}</ref>\n\n==Meaning and spelling==\nAs ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' literally means \"girl\" in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], the equivalent of the Western usage will generally include the term: {{Nihongo|girls' manga|\u5c11\u5973\u6f2b\u753b|sh\u014djo manga}}, or anime for girls ([[:ja:\u5c11\u5973\u5411\u3051\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1|\u5c11\u5973\u5411\u3051\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1]] ''sh\u014djo-muke anime''). The parallel terms ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'', ''[[seinen]]'', and ''[[Josei manga|josei]]'' also occur in the categorization of manga and anime, with similar qualification. Though the terminology originates with the Japanese publishers and advertisers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zakko.or.jp/subwin/pdf/genre.pdf |script-title=ja:\u96d1\u8a8c\u30b8\u30e3\u30f3\u30eb\u304a\u3088\u3073\u30ab\u30c6\u30b4\u30ea\u533a\u5206\u4e00\u89a7 |date=February 15, 2018 |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |trans-title=Magazine genre and category list |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104111150/http://www.zakko.or.jp/subwin/pdf/genre.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref> cultural differences with the West mean that labeling in English tends to vary wildly, with the types often confused and misapplied.\n\nDue to vagaries in the [[romanization of Japanese]], publishers may transcribe {{Nihongo2|\u5c11\u5973}} (written {{Nihongo2|\u3057\u3087\u3046\u3058\u3087}} in ''[[hiragana]]'') in a wide variety of ways. By far the most common form, ''shoujo''{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}, follows [[English phonology]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}, preserves the spelling, and requires only [[ASCII]] input. The [[Hepburn romanization]] ''sh\u014djo'' uses a [[Macron (diacritic)|macron]] for the long vowel, though the prevalence of [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|Latin-1]] fonts often results in a [[circumflex]] instead, as in ''sh\u00f4jo''. Many English-language texts just ignore long vowels, using ''shojo'', potentially leading to confusion with \u51e6\u5973 (''[[Sh\u014djo|shojo]]'', lit. \"virgin\") as well as other possible meanings. Finally, transliterators may use ''[[Nihon-shiki]]''-type mirroring of the ''[[kana]]'' spelling: ''sy\u00f4jyo'', or ''syoujyo''.\n\n==Western adoption==\n{{Original research|date=July 2008}}\nWestern fans classify a wide variety of titles as ''sh\u014djo'', even though their Japanese creators label them differently. Anything non-offensive and featuring female characters may classify as ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as the ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'' comedy series ''[[Azumanga Daioh]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goetz |first1=Melanie |title=MIT Anime Showings: Synopses - Azumanga Daioh |url=http://web.mit.edu/anime/www/Showings/Azumanga_Daioh.shtml |website=MIT Anime Club |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205105824/http://web.mit.edu/anime/www/Showings/Azumanga_Daioh.shtml |archivedate=February 5, 2008 |date=August 19, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, as romance has become a common element of many ''sh\u014djo'' works, any title with romance \u2013 such as the ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'' series ''[[Love Hina]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chobot |first1=Jessica |title=Shojo Showdown: Making sense of the manga genres |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/13/shojo-showdown |website=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104011708/https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/13/shojo-showdown |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |date=December 13, 2005 |url-status=live}}</ref> or the ''[[seinen]]'' series ''[[Oh My Goddess!]]'' \u2013 tend to get mislabeled.\n\nThis confusion also extends beyond the fan community; articles aimed at the mainstream also widely misrepresent the terms. In an introduction to anime and manga, British writer [[Jon Courtenay Grimwood]] writes: \"''[[Maison Ikkoku]]'' comes from [[Rumiko Takahashi]], one of the best-known of all ''sh\u00f4jo'' writers. Imagine a very Japanese equivalent of ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' or ''[[Melrose Place]]''. It has Takahashi's usual and highly successful mix of teenagers and romance, with darker clouds of adolescence hovering.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Grimwood |first1=Jon Courtenay |authorlink1=Jon Courtenay Grimwood |title=Every Picture... |journal=Books Quarterly |date=2006 |issue=19 |page=42}}</ref> Takahashi is a famous ''sh\u014dnen'' [[manga artist]], but ''Maison Ikkoku'', one of her few ''[[Seinen manga|seinen]]'' titles and serialized in ''[[Big Comic Spirits]]'' magazine, is aimed at males in their 20s.\n\n[[Rachel Matt Thorn|Rachel Thorn]], who has made a career out of studying girls' comics, attempts to clarify the matter by explaining that \"''sh\u00f4jo'' manga are manga published in ''sh\u00f4jo'' magazines (as defined by their publishers)\".<ref name=\"Thorn 2004\"/> However, English publishers and stores have problems retailing ''sh\u014djo'' titles, including its spelling. Licensees such as [[Dark Horse Comics]] have misidentified several of the ''seinen'' titles, and in particular, manga and anime intended for a younger audience in Japan often contains violent or mature themes that would be targeted toward an older demographic in the US.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shojo Update: Your Comments and Our Answers |url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/news/654.html |website=[[ICv2]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103235333/https://icv2.com/articles/comics/view/654/shojo-update |archivedate=November 3, 2019 |date=August 22, 2001 |url-status=live}}</ref> In this way licensees often either voluntarily [[censorship|censor]] titles or re-market them toward an older audience. In the less conservative [[Europe]]an markets, content that might be heavily edited or cut in an English-language release often remains in [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], and other translated editions.\n\nAs one effect of these variations, American companies have moved to use the borrowed words that have gained name-value in fan communities, but to separate them from the Japanese meaning. In their ''sh\u014djo'' manga range, publisher [[Viz Media]] attempted a re-appropriation of the term, providing the following definition:\n\n{{quotation |'''sh\u00f4\u00b7jo''' (sho'jo) ''n.'' '''1.''' Manga appealing to both female and male readers. '''2.''' Exciting stories with true-to-life characters and the thrill of exotic locales. '''3.''' Connecting the heart and mind through real human relationships.\n|''[[Here Is Greenwood]]'', Vol. 1 by Yukie Nasu<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nasu |first1=Yukie |title=Here Is Greenwood. ''Vol. 1'' |date=November 8, 2004 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |location=San Francisco, CA |isbn=978-1-59116-604-7}}</ref> |source=}}\n\nThe desire to disassociate the word ''sh\u014djo'' from its meaning, \"girl\", seems{{Original research inline|date=August 2009}} largely driven by fear of putting off potential new readers, particularly male ones.\n\nManga and anime labeled as ''sh\u014djo'' need not only interest girls; some titles gain a following outside the traditional audience. For instance, [[Frederik L. Schodt]] identifies [[Akimi Yoshida]]'s ''[[Banana Fish]]'' as:\n\n{{quotation|...one of the few girls' manga a red-blooded Japanese male adult could admit to reading without blushing. Yoshida, while adhering to the conventions of girls' comics in her emphasis on gay male love, made this possible by eschewing flowers and bug eyes in favor of tight bold strokes, action scenes, and speed lines.<ref name=\"Schodt 1996\"/>}}\n\nHowever, such successful \"crossover\" titles remain the exception rather than the rule: the archetypal ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazine ''[[Hana to Yume]]'' has a 95% female readership, with a majority aged 17 or under.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Hana to Yume'' Readers Data |url=http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_002/pdf/d_hakus_hanat.pdf |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |archivedate=November 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124154521/http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_002/pdf/d_hakus_hanat.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe growing popularity of romantic ''sh\u014djo'' manga in North America encouraged Toronto-based publisher [[Harlequin Enterprises|Harlequin]], in agreement with [[Dark Horse Comics]], to release manga-styled [[Genre fiction#Romance|romantic]] [[comic]]s starting in 2005. Harlequin's executive vice president Pam Laycok stated that the market has \"vast potential\".<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dark Horse to Publish Harlequin Manga |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2005-06-01/dark-horse-to-publish-harlequin-manga |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=June 1, 2005 |archivedate=December 8, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208063352/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2005-06-01/dark-horse-to-publish-harlequin-manga |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Circulation figures==\nThe reported average circulations for some of the top-selling ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines in 2007 included:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Reported circulation\n! First published\n|-\n| ''[[Ciao (magazine)|Ciao]]''\n| 982,834\n| 1977\n|-\n| ''[[Nakayoshi]]''\n| 400,000\n| 1954\n|-\n| ''[[Ribon]]''\n| 376,666\n| 1955\n|-\n| ''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]''\n| 320,000\n| 1964\n|-\n| ''[[Hana to Yume]]''\n| 226,826\n| 1974\n|-\n| ''[[Cookie (manga)|Cookie]]''\n| 200,000\n| 1999\n|-\n| ''Deluxe Margaret''\n| 181,666\n| 1967\n|-\n| ''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]''\n| 177,916\n| 1963\n|-\n| ''[[LaLa]]''\n| 170,833\n| \t1976\n|-\n| ''[[Cheese!]]''\n| 144,750\n| 1996\n|}\n\nFor comparison, circulations for the top-selling magazines in other categories for 2007 included:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Category\n! Magazine Title\n! Reported Circulation\n|-\n| Top-selling [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]''\n| 2,778,750\n|-\n| Top-selling [[seinen manga|''seinen'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[Young Magazine]]''\n| 981,229\n|-\n| Top-selling [[josei manga|''josei'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[You (Japanese magazine)|You]]''\n| 194,791\n|-\n| Top-selling non-manga magazine\n| ''Monthly the Television''\n| 1,018,919\n|}\n\n(Source for all circulation figures: Japan Magazine Publishers Association<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_001/index.html |script-title=ja:\u300c\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf2007\u300d\u767a\u884c\u306e\u3054\u6848\u5185 |trans-title=Information for ''Magazine Data 2007'' |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621081912/http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_001/index.html |archivedate=June 21, 2008 |url-status=dead}} Note: The publication, which relies on information provided by publishers, categorizes the magazine [[Cookie (manga)|''Cookie'']] as ''josei'', but Shueisha's [http://www.s-manga.net/ s-manga.net website] clearly categorizes that magazine as ''sh\u014djo'', hence its categorization here.</ref>)\n\n==''Sh\u014djo'' magazines in Japan==\nIn a strict sense, the term \"''sh\u014djo'' manga\" refers to a manga serialized in a ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazine. The list below contains past and current Japanese ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines, grouped according to their publishers. Such magazines can appear on a variety of schedules, including bi-weekly (''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]'', ''[[Hana to Yume]]'', ''[[Sh\u014djo Comic]]''), monthly (''[[Ribon]]'', ''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]'', ''[[Bessatsu Friend]]'', ''[[LaLa]]''), bi-monthly (''Deluxe Margaret'', ''[[LaLa DX]]'', ''The Dessert''), and quarterly (''Cookie Box'', ''Unpoko'').\n\n===[[Shueisha]]===\n*''[[Ribon]]'' (monthly, 1955\u2013present)\n*''[[Ribon Original]]'' (bi-monthly, 1981\u20132006)\n*''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]'' (weekly, 1963\u2013present) \n*''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]'' (monthly, 1964\u2013present)\n*''Deluxe Margaret'' (bi-monthly, 1967\u20132010)\n*''The Margaret'' (bi-monthly, 1982\u2013present)\n*''Bouquet'' (monthly, 1978\u20132000)\n*''Bouquet Deluxe'' or ''Bouquet DX'' (irregular, 1980\u20132000)\n*''Bouquet Selection'' (1983\u20131990) \u2014 terminated after publishing seven anthology and artist special issues\n*''[[Cookie (manga)|Cookie]]'' (weekly, 2000\u2013present)\n*''Cookie Box'' (quarterly, 2000\u20132009) \u2014 succeeded ''Bouquet Deluxe''\n\n===[[Kodansha]]===\n* ''[[Nakayoshi]]''\n* ''[[Aria (magazine)|Aria]]''\n* ''[[Sh\u014djo Friend]]''\n* ''[[Bessatsu Friend]]''\n* ''[[Dessert (magazine)|Dessert]]''\n* ''The Dessert''\n\n===[[Shogakukan]]===\n*''[[Ciao (magazine)|Ciao]]''\n*''[[ChuChu (magazine)|ChuChu]]''\n*''[[Sh\u014djo Comic]]''\n*''[[Betsucomi]]''\n*''Petit Comic''\n*''[[Cheese!]]''\n*''Pochette''\n\n===[[Hakusensha]]===\n*''[[Hana to Yume]]''\n*''[[Bessatsu Hana to Yume]]''\n*''[[LaLa]]''\n*''[[LaLa DX]]''\n*''[[Melody (magazine)|Melody]]''\n\n===[[Akita Shoten]]===\n* ''[[Princess (magazine)|Princess]]''\n* ''[[Princess Gold]]''\n* ''Petit Princess''\n* ''Mystery Bonita''\n* ''Susperia Mystery''\n* ''Renai Max''\n\n===[[Kadokawa Shoten]]===\n*''[[Monthly Asuka|Asuka]]''\n\n===Web magazine===\n*''Manga Airport''\n\n===[[Shinshokan]]===\n*''Unpoko''\n\n===Outside Japan===\n\n* ''[[Shojo Beat]]'' (2005\u20132009), published in North America by [[Viz Media]]\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Bish\u014djo]]'' (lit. \"beautiful girl\") \u2013 descriptive of the character type rather than the audience\n* [[Class S (genre)|Class S]] \u2013 historical homoerotic genre about passionate friendships between girls for a female audience\n* [[History of manga]]\n* [[Josei manga|''Josei'' manga]] \u2013 intended for adult women\n* [[List of manga magazines#Sh\u014djo magazines|List of ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines]]\n* [[Magical girl]] \u2013 a genre featuring girls with magical powers or who use magic, initially aimed at a young female audience \n* [[Otome game|''Otome'' game]] \u2013 story-based video games targeted towards women, often romantic in nature\n* [[Seinen manga|''Seinen'' manga]] \u2013 intended for adult men\n* [[Sh\u014dnen manga|''Sh\u014dnen'' manga]] \u2013 intended for boys\n* [[Shoujocon]] \u2013 an anime convention held annually from 2000 to 2003\n* ''[[Sunjung manhwa]]'' \u2013 Korean ''sh\u014djo''-style manga\n* ''[[Yaoi]]'' \u2013 homoerotic stories about men in love\n* [[Yuri (genre)|''Yuri'' (genre)]] \u2013 homoerotic stories about women in love\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://users.skynet.be/mangaguide/mgguide.zip Ultimate Manga Guide] ([[ZIP (file format)|zip]]), version 13.6, last modified July 31, 2004\n* [http://www.rawbw.com/~hbv/anime/shouanim.txt ''Sh\u014djo'' Anime List], last modified February 14, 1995\n* {{cite book |last1=Napier |first1=Susan J. |authorlink1=Susan J. Napier |title=Anime from Akira to Princess Mononoke |date=2001 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0-312-23862-9|title-link=Anime from Akira to Princess Mononoke }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=Sh\u00f4jo Manga\u2014Something for the Girls |journal=The Japan Quarterly |publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |location=Tokyo, Japan |date=2001 |volume=48 |issue=3 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170443/https://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/japan_quarterly/index.html}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Garrity |first1=Shaenon K. |authorlink1=Shaenon K. Garrity |title=The Boys of Shojo Manga |date=2008 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090824043758/https://www.comixology.com/articles/52/The-Boys-of-Shojo-Manga |website=Comixology}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Shamoon |first1=Deborah |title=Revolutionary Romance: ''The Rose of Versailles'' and the Transformation of Shojo Manga |journal=[[Mechademia]] |date=2007 |volume=2 |url=http://www.upress.umn.edu/Books/L/lunning_mechademia2.html |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=Minneapolis, MN |pages=3\u201317 |doi=10.1353/mec.0.0009}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Takahashi |first1=Mizuki |editor1-last=MacWilliams |editor1-first=Mark W. |title=Japanese Visual Culture: Explorations in the World of Manga and Anime |chapter=Opening the Closed World of ''Shojo Manga'' |chapter-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103153622/http://www.mesharpe.com/mall/resultsa.asp?Title=Japanese+Visual+Culture%3A+Explorations+in+the+World+of++Manga+and+Anime |date=2008 |publisher=M.E. Sharpe |isbn=978-0-7656-1601-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/japanesevisualcu0000unse }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last1=\u014cgi |first1=Fusami |title=Beyond Shoujo, Blending Gender: Subverting the Homogendered World in Shoujo Manga (Japanese Comics for Girls) |journal=[[International Journal of Comic Art]] |date=2001 |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=151\u2013161}}\n* {{cite book |last=Prough |first=Jennifer S. |title=Straight from the Heart: Gender, Intimacy, and the Cultural Production of Sh\u014djo Manga |publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press|University of Hawai\u02bbi Press]] |location=Honolulu, HI |isbn=978-0-8248-3528-6 |date=2011}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Saito |first1=Kumiko |title=Magic, 'Sh\u014djo', and Metamorphosis: Magical Girl Anime and the Challenges of Changing Gender Identities in Japanese Society |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |date=2014 |volume=73 |issue=1 |pages=143\u2013164 |issn=0021-9118 |jstor=43553398 |doi=10.1017/S0021911813001708}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Toku |editor1-first=Masami |title=International Perspectives on Shojo and Shojo Manga: The Influence of Girl Culture |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=New York, NY |year=2015 |isbn=978-1-138-80948-2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{portalbar|anime|manga}}\n* {{commons category-inline|Sh\u014djo}}\n* {{Wiktionary-inline|\u5c11\u5973}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shojo}}\n[[Category:Sh\u014djo manga| ]]\n[[Category:Anime and manga terminology]]\n[[Category:Women in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Sh\u014djo'' manga}}\n{{short description|Manga aimed at a teenage female readership}}\n{{other uses of|sh\u014djo|Shojo (disambiguation)}}\n{{Anime and manga}}\n[[File:Shoujo November 1910 with translation.jpg|thumb|200px|A simple four-panel manga from the November 1910 issue of ''Sh\u014djo'' magazine (artist unknown)]]\n[[File:Nazo no clover page 7.jpg|thumb|200px|A page from [[Katsuji Matsumoto]]'s groundbreaking 1934 ''sh\u014djo'' manga series, ''The Mysterious Clover'']]\n{{Nihongo|'''''Sh\u014djo''''', '''''shojo''''', or '''''shoujo'' manga'''|\u5c11\u5973\u6f2b\u753b|sh\u014djo manga}} is [[manga]] aimed at a young teen female [[Target audience|target]]-[[Demography|demographic]] readership. The name [[Romanization of Japanese|romanizes]] the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] '''[[wikt:\u5c11\u5973|\u5c11\u5973]]''' ([[wikt:sh\u014djo|''sh\u014djo'']]), literally \"young woman\". ''Sh\u014djo'' manga covers many subjects in a variety of narrative styles, from [[Period piece|historical drama]] to [[science fiction]], often with a focus on romantic relationships or emotions.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\">{{cite magazine |editor1-last=Toku |editor1-first=Masami |date=2005 |title=Shojo Manga: Girl Power! |url=http://www.csuchico.edu/pub/cs/spring_06/feature_03.html |url-status=dead |magazine=Chico Statements Magazine |publisher=[[California State University, Chico]] |isbn=1-886226-10-5 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010233300/http://www.csuchico.edu/pub/cs/spring_06/feature_03.html |archive-date=October 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, however, ''sh\u014djo'' manga does not comprise a style or genre, but rather indicates a [[Target audience|target demographic]].<ref name=\"Thorn 2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219032133/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/japan_quarterly/index.html |archivedate=February 19, 2007 |url-status=dead |journal=The Japan Quarterly |url=http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/japan_quarterly/index.html |title=Sh\u00f4jo Manga\u2014Something for the Girls |volume=48 |issue=3 |publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |location=Tokyo, Japan |date=2001}}</ref><ref name=\"Thorn 2004\">{{cite web |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=What Sh\u00f4jo Manga Are and Are Not: A Quick Guide for the Confused |url=http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/whatisandisnt.php |website=Matt-Thorn.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118080220/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/whatisandisnt.php |archivedate=November 18, 2015 |date=2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nJapanese magazines specifically for girls, known as ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' magazines, first appeared in 1902 with the founding of {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u754c|Sh\u014djo-kai|lit. \"Girls' World\"}} and continued with others such as {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u4e16\u754c|[[Sh\u014djo Sekai]]|lit. \"Girls' World\"}} (1906) and the long-running {{Nihongo||\u5c11\u5973\u306e\u53cb|Sh\u014djo no Tomo|lit. \"Girls' Friend\"}} (1908).<ref name=\"Thorn 2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |script-title=ja:\u660e\u6cbb\uff5e\u662d\u548c \u5c11\u5973\u96d1\u8a8c\u306e\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb |trans-title=Meiji \u2013 Sh\u014dwa: An Introduction to Girls' Magazines |url=https://www.kikuyo-lib.jp/?page_id=119 |website=Kikuy\u014d Town Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104000351/https://www.kikuyo-lib.jp/?page_id=119 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |location=[[Kikuy\u014d, Kumamoto|Kikuy\u014d, Kumamoto, Japan]] |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe roots of the wide-eyed look commonly associated with ''sh\u014djo'' manga date back to ''sh\u014djo'' magazine illustrations during the early 20th century. The most important illustrators associated with this style at the time were [[Yumeji Takehisa]] and particularly [[Jun'ichi Nakahara]], who, influenced by his work as a doll creator, frequently drew female characters with big eyes in the early 20th century. This had a significant influence on early ''sh\u014djo'' manga, evident in the work of influential [[manga artist]]s such as {{ill|Macoto Takahashi (illustrator)|ja|\u9ad8\u6a4b\u771f\u7434|lt=Macoto Takahashi}} and [[Riyoko Ikeda]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j1LLCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=International Perspectives on Shojo and Shojo Manga: The Influence of Girl Culture |editor1-last=Toku |editor1-first=Masami |page=24 |last1=Masuda |first1=Nozomi |chapter=Shojo Manga and Its Acceptance |date=June 5, 2015 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-1-138-80948-2 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nSimple, single-page manga began to appear in these magazines by 1910, and by the 1930s more sophisticated humor-strips had become an essential feature of most girls' magazines. The most popular manga, [[Katsuji Matsumoto]]'s {{Nihongo3||\u304f\u308b\u304f\u308b\u30af\u30eb\u30df\u3061\u3083\u3093|Kurukuru Kurumi-chan}}, debuted on the pages of ''Sh\u014djo no Tomo'' in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=Pre-World War II Sh\u00f4jo Manga and Illustrations |url=http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/prewar_shoujo/index.php |website=Matt-Thorn.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304214610/http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/prewar_shoujo/index.php |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> As [[World War II]] progressed, however, \"comics, perhaps regarded as frivolous, began to disappear\".<ref name=\"Schodt 1983\">{{cite book |last1=Schodt |first1=Frederik L. |authorlink1=Frederik L. Schodt |title=Manga! Manga! The World of Japanese Comics |date=January 25, 2013 |orig-year=First published in 1983 |publisher=[[Kodansha USA]] |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-56836-476-6|title-link=Manga! Manga! The World of Japanese Comics }}</ref>\n\nPostwar ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as [[Shosuke Kurakane]]'s popular {{Nihongo3||\u3042\u3093\u307f\u3064\u59eb|[[Anmitsu Hime]]|lit. \"Princess Anmitsu\"}},<ref>[[Yoshihiro Yonezawa|Yonezawa, Yoshihiro]], ed. (1991). {{Nihongo3|\"A Children's History of Showa-Era Japan: The World of Sh\u014djo Manga I, 1945\u20131962\"|\u5b50\u4f9b\u306e\u662d\u548c\u53f2\u2500\u2500\u5c11\u5973\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u306e\u4e16\u754c I \u662d\u548c20\u5e74\u301c37\u5e74|Kodomo no Sh\u014dwa-shi: Sh\u014djo manga no sekai I, Sh\u014dwa 20 nen \u2013 37 nen}}. Bessatsu Taiy\u014d series. Tokyo, Japan: Heibonsha. {{ISBN|978-4-582-94239-2}}.</ref> initially followed the pre-war pattern of simple humor-strips. But [[Osamu Tezuka]]'s postwar revolution, introducing intense drama and serious themes to children's manga, spread quickly to ''sh\u014djo'' manga, particularly after the enormous success of his seminal {{Nihongo|''[[Princess Knight]]''|\u30ea\u30dc\u30f3\u306e\u9a0e\u58eb|Ribon no Kishi}}.<ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/>\n\nUntil the mid-1960s, men vastly outnumbered the women (for example: [[Toshiko Ueda]], [[Hideko Mizuno]], [[Masako Watanabe]], and [[Miyako Maki]]) among the artists working on ''sh\u014djo'' manga. Many male manga artists, such as [[Tetsuya Chiba]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=The Moto Hagio Interview |publisher=[[Fantagraphics Books]] |journal=[[The Comics Journal]] |issue=269 |date=2005 |location=Seattle, WA |url=http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/hagio_interview.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113194502/http://www.matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/hagio_interview.php |archivedate=January 13, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> functioned as rookies, waiting for an opportunity to move over to [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' (\u5c11\u5e74 \"boys'\") manga]]. Chiba asked his wife about girls' feelings for research for his manga. At this time, conventional job opportunities for Japanese women did not include becoming a manga artist.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Toku |first1=Masami |title=Shojo Manga! Girls' Comics! A Mirror of Girls' Dreams |journal=[[Mechademia]] |date=2007 |volume=2 |pages=22\u201323 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=Minneapolis, MN |url=http://www.upress.umn.edu/Books/L/lunning_mechademia2.html |issn=19342489}}</ref> Adapting Tezuka's dynamic style to ''sh\u014djo'' manga (which had always been domestic in nature) proved challenging. According to [[Rachel Matt Thorn|Rachel Thorn]]:\n\n<blockquote>While some chose to simply create longer humor-strips, others turned to popular girls' novels of the day as a model for melodramatic ''sh\u014djo'' manga. These manga featured sweet, innocent pre-teen heroines, torn from the safety of family and tossed from one perilous circumstance to another, until finally rescued (usually by a kind, handsome young man) and re-united with their families.<ref>[[Rachel Matt Thorn|Thorn, Rachel Matt]] (March 15, 2008). \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160108135716/http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/colloque/index.php The Multi-Faceted Universe of Sh\u014djo Manga]\". Presented at ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090902061831/http://www.mcjp.asso.fr/pjanv2008/conferences/manga/index.html Le manga, 60 ans apr\u00e8s...]''. Paris, France. Archived from [http://matt-thorn.com/shoujo_manga/colloque/index.php the original] on January 8, 2016.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThese early ''sh\u014djo'' manga almost invariably had pre-adolescent girls as both heroines and readers. Unless they used a fantastic setting (as in ''Princess Knight'') or a backdrop of a distant time or place, romantic love for the heroine remained essentially taboo. But the average age of the readership rose, and its interests changed. In the mid-1960s one of the few female artists in the field, [[Yoshiko Nishitani]], began to draw stories featuring contemporary Japanese teenagers in love. This signaled a dramatic transformation of the genre.<ref name=\"Yonezawa 1991\">[[Yoshihiro Yonezawa|Yonezawa, Yoshihiro]], ed. (1991). {{Nihongo3|\"A Children's History of Showa-Era Japan: The World of Sh\u014djo Manga II, 1963\u20131989\"|\u5b50\u4f9b\u306e\u662d\u548c\u53f2\u2500\u2500\u5c11\u5973\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u306e\u4e16\u754c II \u662d\u548c38\u5e74\u301c64\u5e74|Kodomo no Sh\u014dwa-shi: Sh\u014djo manga no sekai II, Sh\u014dwa 38 nen \u2013 64 nen}}. Bessatsu Taiy\u014d series. Tokyo, Japan: Heibonsha. {{ISBN|978-4-582-94240-8}}.</ref><ref name=\"Thorn 2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=The Magnificent Forty-Niners |issue=269 |date=2005 |journal=[[The Comics Journal]] |publisher=[[Fantagraphics Books]] |location=Seattle, WA |url=https://www.en.matt-thorn.com/single-post/2017/05/31/The-Magnificent-Forty-Niners |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102223859/https://www.en.matt-thorn.com/single-post/2017/05/31/The-Magnificent-Forty-Niners |archivedate=November 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This may have been due to the [[baby boomers]] becoming teens, and the industry trying to keep them as readers.<ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/>\n\nBetween 1950 and 1969, increasingly large audiences for manga emerged in Japan with the solidification of its two main marketing genres, [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] aimed at adolescent boys and ''sh\u014djo'' manga aimed at adolescent girls.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\"/><ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/> These romantic comedy ''sh\u014djo'' manga were inspired by American TV dramas of the time.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saito |first1=Kumiko |title=Desire in Subtext: Gender, Fandom, and Women's Male-Male Homoerotic Parodies in Contemporary Japan |journal=[[Mechademia]] |volume=6 |page=173 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=Minneapolis, MN |url=https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/mechademia-6 |issn=1934-2489 |date=2011}}</ref> The success of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, and the gold medal won by the [[Japan women's national volleyball team]], influenced a series of sports ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as {{Nihongo|''[[Attack No. 1]]''|\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30afNo.1|Atakku Nanb\u0101 Wan}}. On December 5, 1966, the first ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' [[anime]] series, {{Nihongo|''[[Sally the Witch]]''|\u9b54\u6cd5\u4f7f\u3044\u30b5\u30ea\u30fc|Mah\u014dtsukai Sar\u012b}}, premiered in Japan on [[TV Asahi|NET TV]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Witches in Anime |url=http://www.mindspring.com/~theduffields/resume/articles/features/witches.htm |newspaper=[[Animerica Extra]] |volume=3 |issue=11 |date=October 2000 |last1=Duffield |first1=Patricia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103230229/http://www.mindspring.com/~theduffields/resume/articles/features/witches.htm |archive-date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 1967, ''sh\u014djo'' manga began being published in ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' format.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=K\u00e1lovics |first1=Dalma |url=http://www.kyoto-seika.ac.jp/researchlab/wp/wp-content/uploads/sa_dalma_kalovics1.pdf |title=The missing link of sh\u014djo manga history: the changes in 60s sh\u014djo manga as seen through the magazine ''Sh\u016bkan Margaret'' |journal=Ky\u014dto Seika Daigaku Kiy\u014d |issue=49 |publisher=[[Kyoto Seika University]] |date=2016 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104101525/http://www.kyoto-seika.ac.jp/researchlab/wp/wp-content/uploads/sa_dalma_kalovics1.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween roughly 1969 and 1971, a flood of young female manga artists transformed the genre again. Some, including [[Moto Hagio]], [[Yumiko \u014cshima]], and [[Keiko Takemiya]], became known as the {{Nihongo|[[Year 24 Group]]|24\u5e74\u7d44|Nij\u016byo-nen Gumi}}, or the {{Nihongo|Fabulous Year 24 Group|\u82b1\u306e24\u5e74\u7d44|Hana no Nij\u016byo-nen Gumi}}, so named from the approximate year of birth many of them shared: [[Sh\u014dwa period|Sh\u014dwa]] 24, or 1949. This loosely defined group experimented with content and form, inventing such subgenres such as ''[[sh\u014dnen-ai]]'' (boys' love), and earning the long-maligned ''sh\u014djo'' manga unprecedented critical praise.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Contemporary Japanese Women's Theatre and Visual Arts|last=Anan|first=Nobuko|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=9781349557066|location=London|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137372987}}</ref> Other female artists of the same generation, such as [[Riyoko Ikeda]], [[Yukari Ichijo]], and [[Sumika Yamamoto]], garnered unprecedented popular support with such hits (respectively) as {{Nihongo|''[[The Rose of Versailles]]''|\u30d9\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30e6\u306e\u3070\u3089|Berusaiyu no Bara}}, {{Nihongo3||\u30c7\u30b6\u30a4\u30ca\u30fc|Dezainaa|lit. \"Designer\"}}, and {{Nihongo|''[[Aim for the Ace!]]''|\u30a8\u30fc\u30b9\u3092\u306d\u3089\u3048!|\u0112su o Nerae!}}.<ref name=\"Toku 2005\"/><ref name=\"Thorn 2001\"/><ref name=\"Yonezawa 1991\"/><ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/><ref name=\"Schodt 1983\"/><ref name=\"Manga Sixty Years 1\">{{cite book |last1=Gravett |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Gravett |title=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics |date=July 19, 2004 |publisher=Harper Design |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-85669-391-2 |pages=78\u201380|title-link=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics }}</ref><ref>Lent, 2001, ''op. cit.'', pp. 9\u201310.</ref>{{Volume needed|date=January 2010}} During that era, women's roles in Japanese society were changing, and women were being elected to the [[National Diet]], and publishers responded by employing more female talent.<ref name=\"Thorn 2005\"/>  Since the mid-1970s, women have created the vast majority of ''sh\u014djo'' manga; notable exceptions include [[Patariro|Mineo Maya]] and [[Shinji Wada]].\n\nFrom 1975, ''sh\u014djo'' manga continued to develop stylistically while simultaneously branching out into different but overlapping subgenres.<ref name=\"\u014cgi\">{{cite journal |last1=\u014cgi |first1=Fusami |url=http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/content/BPL_images/Journal_Samples2/JPCU0022-3840~36~4/045.PDF |title=Female Subjectivity and ''Shoujo'' (Girls) ''Manga'' (Japanese Comics): ''Shoujo'' in Ladies' Comics and Young Ladies' Comics |journal=[[The Journal of Popular Culture]] |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell|Blackwell Publishing]] |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=780\u2013803 |date=2003 |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104101314/http://www.blackwellpublishing.com/content/BPL_images/Journal_Samples2/JPCU0022-3840~36~4/045.PDF |url-status=live|doi=10.1111/1540-5931.00045 }}</ref> [[Meiji University]] professor [[Yukari Fujimoto]] writes that during the 1990s, ''sh\u014djo'' manga became concerned with self-fulfillment. She intimates that the 1990\u20131991 [[Gulf War]] influenced the development of female characters \"who fight to protect the destiny of a community\", such as ''[[Red River (manga)|Red River]]'', ''[[Basara (manga)|Basara]]'', ''[[Magic Knight Rayearth]]'', and ''[[Sailor Moon]]''. Fujimoto opines that the ''sh\u014djo'' manga of the 1990s depicted emotional bonds between women as stronger than the bonds between a man and a woman.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Fujimoto |first1=Yukari |authorlink1=Yukari Fujimoto |date=2008 |title=Japanese Contemporary Manga (Number 1): ''Sh\u014djo'' (Girls Manga) |url=http://www.jpf.go.jp/JF_Contents/GetImage/img_pdf/JBN56.pdf?ContentNo=9&SubsystemNo=1&FileName=img_pdf/JBN56.pdf |language= |magazine=Japanese Book News |volume=56 |page=12 |publisher=[[Japan Foundation|The Japan Foundation]] |accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Major subgenres include romance, science fiction, fantasy, [[magical girls]], ''[[yaoi]]'', and \"[[Josei manga|ladies comics]]\" (in Japanese, ''redisu'' \u30ec\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30b9, ''redikomi'' \u30ec\u30c7\u30a3\u30b3\u30df, and ''josei'' \u5973\u6027).<ref name=\"Manga Sixty Years 2\">{{cite book |last1=Gravett |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Gravett |title=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics |date=July 19, 2004 |publisher=Harper Design |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-1-85669-391-2 |page=8|title-link=Manga: Sixty Years of Japanese Comics }}</ref><ref name=\"Schodt 1996\">{{cite book |last1=Schodt |first1=Frederik L. |authorlink1=Frederik L. Schodt |title=Dreamland Japan: Writings on Modern Manga |date=1996 |publisher=Stone Bridge Press |location=Berkeley, CA |isbn=978-1-880656-23-5|title-link=Dreamland Japan }}</ref>\n\n==Meaning and spelling==\nAs ''[[sh\u014djo]]'' literally means \"girl\" in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], the equivalent of the Western usage will generally include the term: {{Nihongo|girls' manga|\u5c11\u5973\u6f2b\u753b|sh\u014djo manga}}, or anime for girls ([[:ja:\u5c11\u5973\u5411\u3051\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1|\u5c11\u5973\u5411\u3051\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1]] ''sh\u014djo-muke anime''). The parallel terms ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'', ''[[seinen]]'', and ''[[Josei manga|josei]]'' also occur in the categorization of manga and anime, with similar qualification. Though the terminology originates with the Japanese publishers and advertisers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zakko.or.jp/subwin/pdf/genre.pdf |script-title=ja:\u96d1\u8a8c\u30b8\u30e3\u30f3\u30eb\u304a\u3088\u3073\u30ab\u30c6\u30b4\u30ea\u533a\u5206\u4e00\u89a7 |date=February 15, 2018 |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |trans-title=Magazine genre and category list |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104111150/http://www.zakko.or.jp/subwin/pdf/genre.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref> cultural differences with the West mean that labeling in English tends to vary wildly, with the types often confused and misapplied.\n\nDue to vagaries in the [[romanization of Japanese]], publishers may transcribe {{Nihongo2|\u5c11\u5973}} (written {{Nihongo2|\u3057\u3087\u3046\u3058\u3087}} in ''[[hiragana]]'') in a wide variety of ways. By far the most common form, ''shoujo''{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}, follows [[English phonology]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}, preserves the spelling, and requires only [[ASCII]] input. The [[Hepburn romanization]] ''sh\u014djo'' uses a [[Macron (diacritic)|macron]] for the long vowel, though the prevalence of [[ISO/IEC 8859-1|Latin-1]] fonts often results in a [[circumflex]] instead, as in ''sh\u00f4jo''. Many English-language texts just ignore long vowels, using ''shojo'', potentially leading to confusion with \u51e6\u5973 (''[[Sh\u014djo|shojo]]'', lit. \"virgin\") as well as other possible meanings. Finally, transliterators may use ''[[Nihon-shiki]]''-type mirroring of the ''[[kana]]'' spelling: ''sy\u00f4jyo'', or ''syoujyo''.\n\n==Western adoption==\n{{Original research|date=July 2008}}\nWestern fans classify a wide variety of titles as ''sh\u014djo'', even though their Japanese creators label them differently. Anything non-offensive and featuring female characters may classify as ''sh\u014djo'' manga, such as the ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'' comedy series ''[[Azumanga Daioh]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goetz |first1=Melanie |title=MIT Anime Showings: Synopses - Azumanga Daioh |url=http://web.mit.edu/anime/www/Showings/Azumanga_Daioh.shtml |website=MIT Anime Club |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205105824/http://web.mit.edu/anime/www/Showings/Azumanga_Daioh.shtml |archivedate=February 5, 2008 |date=August 19, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, as romance has become a common element of many ''sh\u014djo'' works, any title with romance \u2013 such as the ''[[sh\u014dnen]]'' series ''[[Love Hina]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chobot |first1=Jessica |title=Shojo Showdown: Making sense of the manga genres |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/13/shojo-showdown |website=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104011708/https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/12/13/shojo-showdown |archivedate=November 4, 2019 |date=December 13, 2005 |url-status=live}}</ref> or the ''[[seinen]]'' series ''[[Oh My Goddess!]]'' \u2013 tend to get mislabeled.\n\nThis confusion also extends beyond the fan community; articles aimed at the mainstream also widely misrepresent the terms. In an introduction to anime and manga, British writer [[Jon Courtenay Grimwood]] writes: \"''[[Maison Ikkoku]]'' comes from [[Rumiko Takahashi]], one of the best-known of all ''sh\u00f4jo'' writers. Imagine a very Japanese equivalent of ''[[Sweet Valley High]]'' or ''[[Melrose Place]]''. It has Takahashi's usual and highly successful mix of teenagers and romance, with darker clouds of adolescence hovering.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Grimwood |first1=Jon Courtenay |authorlink1=Jon Courtenay Grimwood |title=Every Picture... |journal=Books Quarterly |date=2006 |issue=19 |page=42}}</ref> Takahashi is a famous ''sh\u014dnen'' [[manga artist]], but ''Maison Ikkoku'', one of her few ''[[Seinen manga|seinen]]'' titles and serialized in ''[[Big Comic Spirits]]'' magazine, is aimed at males in their 20s.\n\n[[Rachel Matt Thorn|Rachel Thorn]], who has made a career out of studying girls' comics, attempts to clarify the matter by explaining that \"''sh\u00f4jo'' manga are manga published in ''sh\u00f4jo'' magazines (as defined by their publishers)\".<ref name=\"Thorn 2004\"/> However, English publishers and stores have problems retailing ''sh\u014djo'' titles, including its spelling. Licensees such as [[Dark Horse Comics]] have misidentified several of the ''seinen'' titles, and in particular, manga and anime intended for a younger audience in Japan often contains violent or mature themes that would be targeted toward an older demographic in the US.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shojo Update: Your Comments and Our Answers |url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/news/654.html |website=[[ICv2]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103235333/https://icv2.com/articles/comics/view/654/shojo-update |archivedate=November 3, 2019 |date=August 22, 2001 |url-status=live}}</ref> In this way licensees often either voluntarily [[censorship|censor]] titles or re-market them toward an older audience. In the less conservative [[Europe]]an markets, content that might be heavily edited or cut in an English-language release often remains in [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], and other translated editions.\n\nAs one effect of these variations, American companies have moved to use the borrowed words that have gained name-value in fan communities, but to separate them from the Japanese meaning. In their ''sh\u014djo'' manga range, publisher [[Viz Media]] attempted a re-appropriation of the term, providing the following definition:\n\n{{quotation |'''sh\u00f4\u00b7jo''' (sho'jo) ''n.'' '''1.''' Manga appealing to both female and male readers. '''2.''' Exciting stories with true-to-life characters and the thrill of exotic locales. '''3.''' Connecting the heart and mind through real human relationships.\n|''[[Here Is Greenwood]]'', Vol. 1 by Yukie Nasu<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nasu |first1=Yukie |title=Here Is Greenwood. ''Vol. 1'' |date=November 8, 2004 |publisher=[[Viz Media]] |location=San Francisco, CA |isbn=978-1-59116-604-7}}</ref> |source=}}\n\nThe desire to disassociate the word ''sh\u014djo'' from its meaning, \"girl\", seems{{Original research inline|date=August 2009}} largely driven by fear of putting off potential new readers, particularly male ones.\n\nManga and anime labeled as ''sh\u014djo'' need not only interest girls; some titles gain a following outside the traditional audience. For instance, [[Frederik L. Schodt]] identifies [[Akimi Yoshida]]'s ''[[Banana Fish]]'' as:\n\n{{quotation|...one of the few girls' manga a red-blooded Japanese male adult could admit to reading without blushing. Yoshida, while adhering to the conventions of girls' comics in her emphasis on gay male love, made this possible by eschewing flowers and bug eyes in favor of tight bold strokes, action scenes, and speed lines.<ref name=\"Schodt 1996\"/>}}\n\nHowever, such successful \"crossover\" titles remain the exception rather than the rule: the archetypal ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazine ''[[Hana to Yume]]'' has a 95% female readership, with a majority aged 17 or under.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Hana to Yume'' Readers Data |url=http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_002/pdf/d_hakus_hanat.pdf |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |archivedate=November 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124154521/http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_002/pdf/d_hakus_hanat.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe growing popularity of romantic ''sh\u014djo'' manga in North America encouraged Toronto-based publisher [[Harlequin Enterprises|Harlequin]], in agreement with [[Dark Horse Comics]], to release manga-styled [[Genre fiction#Romance|romantic]] [[comic]]s starting in 2005. Harlequin's executive vice president Pam Laycok stated that the market has \"vast potential\".<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dark Horse to Publish Harlequin Manga |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2005-06-01/dark-horse-to-publish-harlequin-manga |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=June 1, 2005 |archivedate=December 8, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208063352/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2005-06-01/dark-horse-to-publish-harlequin-manga |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Circulation figures==\nThe reported average circulations for some of the top-selling ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines in 2007 included:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Reported circulation\n! First published\n|-\n| ''[[Ciao (magazine)|Ciao]]''\n| 982,834\n| 1977\n|-\n| ''[[Nakayoshi]]''\n| 400,000\n| 1954\n|-\n| ''[[Ribon]]''\n| 376,666\n| 1955\n|-\n| ''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]''\n| 320,000\n| 1964\n|-\n| ''[[Hana to Yume]]''\n| 226,826\n| 1974\n|-\n| ''[[Cookie (manga)|Cookie]]''\n| 200,000\n| 1999\n|-\n| ''Deluxe Margaret''\n| 181,666\n| 1967\n|-\n| ''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]''\n| 177,916\n| 1963\n|-\n| ''[[LaLa]]''\n| 170,833\n| \t1976\n|-\n| ''[[Cheese!]]''\n| 144,750\n| 1996\n|}\n\nFor comparison, circulations for the top-selling magazines in other categories for 2007 included:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Category\n! Magazine Title\n! Reported Circulation\n|-\n| Top-selling [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]''\n| 2,778,750\n|-\n| Top-selling [[seinen manga|''seinen'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[Young Magazine]]''\n| 981,229\n|-\n| Top-selling [[josei manga|''josei'' manga]] magazine\n| ''[[You (Japanese magazine)|You]]''\n| 194,791\n|-\n| Top-selling non-manga magazine\n| ''Monthly the Television''\n| 1,018,919\n|}\n\n(Source for all circulation figures: Japan Magazine Publishers Association<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_001/index.html |script-title=ja:\u300c\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf2007\u300d\u767a\u884c\u306e\u3054\u6848\u5185 |trans-title=Information for ''Magazine Data 2007'' |publisher=Japan Magazine Publishers Association |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621081912/http://www.j-magazine.or.jp/data_001/index.html |archivedate=June 21, 2008 |url-status=dead}} Note: The publication, which relies on information provided by publishers, categorizes the magazine [[Cookie (manga)|''Cookie'']] as ''josei'', but Shueisha's [http://www.s-manga.net/ s-manga.net website] clearly categorizes that magazine as ''sh\u014djo'', hence its categorization here.</ref>)\n\n==''Sh\u014djo'' magazines in Japan==\nIn a strict sense, the term \"''sh\u014djo'' manga\" refers to a manga serialized in a ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazine. The list below contains past and current Japanese ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines, grouped according to their publishers. Such magazines can appear on a variety of schedules, including bi-weekly (''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]'', ''[[Hana to Yume]]'', ''[[Sh\u014djo Comic]]''), monthly (''[[Ribon]]'', ''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]'', ''[[Bessatsu Friend]]'', ''[[LaLa]]''), bi-monthly (''Deluxe Margaret'', ''[[LaLa DX]]'', ''The Dessert''), and quarterly (''Cookie Box'', ''Unpoko'').\n\n===[[Shueisha]]===\n*''[[Ribon]]'' (monthly, 1955\u2013present)\n*''[[Ribon Original]]'' (bi-monthly, 1981\u20132006)\n*''[[Margaret (magazine)|Margaret]]'' (weekly, 1963\u2013present) \n*''[[Bessatsu Margaret]]'' (monthly, 1964\u2013present)\n*''Deluxe Margaret'' (bi-monthly, 1967\u20132010)\n*''The Margaret'' (bi-monthly, 1982\u2013present)\n*''Bouquet'' (monthly, 1978\u20132000)\n*''Bouquet Deluxe'' or ''Bouquet DX'' (irregular, 1980\u20132000)\n*''Bouquet Selection'' (1983\u20131990) \u2014 terminated after publishing seven anthology and artist special issues\n*''[[Cookie (manga)|Cookie]]'' (weekly, 2000\u2013present)\n*''Cookie Box'' (quarterly, 2000\u20132009) \u2014 succeeded ''Bouquet Deluxe''\n\n===[[Kodansha]]===\n* ''[[Nakayoshi]]''\n* ''[[Aria (magazine)|Aria]]''\n* ''[[Sh\u014djo Friend]]''\n* ''[[Bessatsu Friend]]''\n* ''[[Dessert (magazine)|Dessert]]''\n* ''The Dessert''\n\n===[[Shogakukan]]===\n*''[[Ciao (magazine)|Ciao]]''\n*''[[ChuChu (magazine)|ChuChu]]''\n*''[[Sh\u014djo Comic]]''\n*''[[Betsucomi]]''\n*''Petit Comic''\n*''[[Cheese!]]''\n*''Pochette''\n\n===[[Hakusensha]]===\n*''[[Hana to Yume]]''\n*''[[Bessatsu Hana to Yume]]''\n*''[[LaLa]]''\n*''[[LaLa DX]]''\n*''[[Melody (magazine)|Melody]]''\n\n===[[Akita Shoten]]===\n* ''[[Princess (magazine)|Princess]]''\n* ''[[Princess Gold]]''\n* ''Petit Princess''\n* ''Mystery Bonita''\n* ''Susperia Mystery''\n* ''Renai Max''\n\n===[[Kadokawa Shoten]]===\n*''[[Monthly Asuka|Asuka]]''\n\n===Web magazine===\n*''Manga Airport''\n\n===[[Shinshokan]]===\n*''Unpoko''\n\n===Outside Japan===\n\n* ''[[Shojo Beat]]'' (2005\u20132009), published in North America by [[Viz Media]]\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Bish\u014djo]]'' (lit. \"beautiful girl\") \u2013 descriptive of the character type rather than the audience\n* [[Class S (genre)|Class S]] \u2013 historical homoerotic genre about passionate friendships between girls for a female audience\n* [[History of manga]]\n* [[Josei manga|''Josei'' manga]] \u2013 intended for adult women\n* [[List of manga magazines#Sh\u014djo magazines|List of ''sh\u014djo'' manga magazines]]\n* [[Magical girl]] \u2013 a genre featuring girls with magical powers or who use magic, initially aimed at a young female audience \n* [[Otome game|''Otome'' game]] \u2013 story-based video games targeted towards women, often romantic in nature\n* [[Seinen manga|''Seinen'' manga]] \u2013 intended for adult men\n* [[Sh\u014dnen manga|''Sh\u014dnen'' manga]] \u2013 intended for boys\n* [[Shoujocon]] \u2013 an anime convention held annually from 2000 to 2003\n* ''[[Sunjung manhwa]]'' \u2013 Korean ''sh\u014djo''-style manga\n* ''[[Yaoi]]'' \u2013 homoerotic stories about men in love\n* [[Yuri (genre)|''Yuri'' (genre)]] \u2013 homoerotic stories about women in love\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://users.skynet.be/mangaguide/mgguide.zip Ultimate Manga Guide] ([[ZIP (file format)|zip]]), version 13.6, last modified July 31, 2004\n* [http://www.rawbw.com/~hbv/anime/shouanim.txt ''Sh\u014djo'' Anime List], last modified February 14, 1995\n* {{cite book |last1=Napier |first1=Susan J. |authorlink1=Susan J. Napier |title=Anime from Akira to Princess Mononoke |date=2001 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0-312-23862-9|title-link=Anime from Akira to Princess Mononoke }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thorn |first1=Rachel Matt |authorlink1=Rachel Matt Thorn |title=Sh\