ernal links==\n{{Commons category|Classical music of India}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.parrikar.org Rajan Parrikar Music Archive] includes detailed articles on Indian classical music with analyses and audio extracts from rare recordings.\n*[http://www.parrikar.org/vpl/ Vijaya Parrikar Library of Indian Classical Music] Library contains recorded music of India's great music masters of yesteryear, excerpts of old, hard-to-find or unpublished recordings.\n* [http://www.moutal.eu/indian-music.html Hindustani Rag Sangeet Online \u2013 more than 800 audio and video archives]\n* [https://raag-hindustani.com/ Raag Hindustani] \u2013 Explanations and examples of Indian Classical (Hindustani) music\n* [http://www.spicmacay.com/about Classical Indian music], SPIC MACAY\n\n{{Indian Music}}\n{{Indian musical instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Indian classical music| ]]\n", "name_user": "\"vinaytaneja9\"", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFeatures:or every nation have there own musical culture like Bangladeshi music, Pakistani music, Nepali music, in India [https://www.indianclassicalmusic9.com/ Indian classical music] &)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_classical_music"}
{"title_page": "Big Tech", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Label of large technology companies including Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft}}\n{{expand french|GAFAM|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:10 Largest Corporations by Market Capitalization.png|thumb|400x400px|10 largest corporations by market capitalization]]\nThe term '''\"Big Tech\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/82dff4a4-3283-11e8-ac48-10c6fdc22f03|title=The Economics of Big Tech|date=2018-03-29|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>, along with its synonym '''\"Tech Giants\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/13/magazine/internet-platform.html|title=We\u2019re Stuck With the Tech Giants. But They\u2019re Stuck With Each Other.|date=2019-11-13|website=New York Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, has been used in [[journalism]] to refer to the largest and most dominant [[Company|companies]] in the [[information technology]] industry.\n\nBy the end of the [[2010s]], five [[United States of America|American]] [[technology company|technology companies]]{{snd}}[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Google]], [[Facebook, Inc.|Facebook]], and [[Microsoft]]{{snd}}were, besides [[Saudi Aramco]], the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|most valuable public companies globally]].<ref name=\"FXSSI most valuable companies globally, Jan 2020\">{{cite web |title=Most Valuable Companies in the World - 2020 |url=https://fxssi.com/top-10-most-valuable-companies-in-the-world |website=FXSSI - Forex Sentiment Board |accessdate=27 January 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/l8mID |archivedate=27 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> At different points, the maximum market capitalization of each of these five technology companies has ranged from around $500 billion to around $1.4 trillion [[United States dollar|USD]]. These companies, specifically Amazon, Apple, Google and Facebook, have been the center of regulatory pressure from the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and [[Federal Trade Commission]] because of concerns over monopolistic practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/2/6/21125026/big-tech-congress-antitrust-investigation-amazon-apple-google-facebook|title=Why Congress\u2019s antitrust investigation should make Big Tech nervous|last=Rey|first=Jason Del|date=2020-02-06|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pymnts.com/antitrust/2019/doj-to-wrap-up-probe-into-facebook-google-amazon-apple-in-2020/|title=DOJ To Wrap Up Probe Into Big Tech In 2020|last=PYMNTS|date=2019-12-11|website=PYMNTS.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/big-tech-s-antitrust-wipeout-33-billion-erased-from-the-value-of-amazon-apple-facebook-and-google-after-doj-announces-probe-1028379566|title=The DOJ's latest probe erased $33 billion from Amazon, Apple, Facebook, and Google {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> There were also two [[China|Chinese]] technology companies in the top ten most valuable publicly traded companies globally at the end of the 2010s, which were [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] and [[Tencent]].\n\nThe biggest American technology companies have replaced the energy giants such as [[Exxon Mobil]], [[BP]], [[Gazprom]], [[PetroChina]] and [[Royal Dutch Shell]] (so-called \"[[Big Oil]]\") from the first decade of the 21st century at the top of the [[NASDAQ]] stock index. They have also outpaced the traditional big media companies such as [[Disney]], [[AT&T]], [[Comcast]] and [[21st Century Fox]] (the so-called \"[[Big Media]]\") by a factor of 10.<ref>{{Citation |title=Tech Giants, Artificial Intelligence, and the Future of Journalism (Open Access) |author=Jason Paul Whittaker |publisher=Routledge |date=Feb 11, 2019 |chapter=Introduction}}</ref> In 2017, the five biggest American IT companies had a combined valuation of over $3.3 trillion, and made up more than 40 percent of the value of the [[Nasdaq 100]].<ref name=\"big5\">{{Citation |title=The 'Big Five' Could Destroy the Tech Ecosystem |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-11-15/the-big-five-could-destroy-the-tech-ecosystem}}</ref>\nThere has been speculation that it may not be possible to live day-to-day in the digital world outside of the ecosystem created by the five biggest tech companies (by market capitalisation).<ref>{{Citation |title=It\u2019s almost impossible to function without the big five tech giants |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/feb/17/almost-impossible-to-function-without-big-five-tech-giants}}</ref> Some have also raised the issue of regulating their influence in the areas of privacy, market power, free speech and censorship (including inappropriate content), and national security and law enforcement.<ref>{{Citation |title=Privacy, power and censorship: how to regulate big tech |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/apr/29/big-tech-regulation-facebook-google-amazon}}</ref> On the other hand, by providing cheap or even free services to consumers, they remain popular.<ref name=\"vox\">{{Citation |title=The push to break up Big Tech, explained |first=Matthew |last=Yglesias |authorlink=Matt Yglesias |date=May 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/5/3/18520703/big-tech-break-up-explained}}</ref>\n\nOther big technology companies on a global scale include [[Samsung]], [[Intel]], [[IBM]], [[Cisco Systems]], [[Tencent]] and [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]]. Along with Apple, Google, Facebook, and Microsoft, they completed the list of top ten technology companies in the world at the end of 2010s, according to the Forbes Global 2000 list published in 2019, an evaluation based on annual sales, profit, assets, market capitalization, and overall market valuation (Amazon and Alibaba were considered retail companies by Forbes).<ref>{{Citation |title= The Largest Technology Companies In 2019: Apple Reigns As Smartphones Slip And Cloud Services Thrive |author=Jonathan Ponciano |date=May 15, 2019 |publisher= Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonathanponciano/2019/05/15/worlds-largest-tech-companies-2019/#7bac53ea734f}}</ref> \n\n== Membership and definitions ==\nThere have been different definitions and names for the groups of largest companies by different authors. The terms \"Big Four\" and \"Big Five\" are frequently used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/what-are-the-big-four-tech-companies-in-the-us.html|title=What are the Four Big Tech Companies in the US?|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>  One grouping includes Google, Apple, Facebook, and Amazon, which has been called \"GAFA\",<ref name=\"accenture_banking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.accenture.com/us-en/insight-digital-banking-beyond-everyday-bank|title=GAFA Approach to Digital Banking Transformation - Accenture|website=www.accenture.com|language=en}}</ref> the \"Gang of Four\" (after the [[Gang of Four]] political faction in China),<ref name=\"Simon_redefined\" /><ref name=\"gang4_schmidt\" /> and the \"Four Horsemen\" (after the [[Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marketingjournal.org/the-four-horsemen-an-interview-with-scott-galloway/|title=\u201cThe Four Horsemen\u201d \u2013 An Interview with Scott Galloway}}</ref> A more inclusive grouping, GAFAM, defines Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft as \"Big Tech\" due to their success in the stock market.<ref name=\"Financial Times article on MAGA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c817306c-914e-11e8-b639-7680cedcc421|title=Move over Faangs, make way for Maga|last=Waters|first=Richard|date=27 July 2018|website=Financial Times|access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC article on MAGA\">{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=Pippa |title=Four 'MAGA' stocks are worth a combined $4 trillion. Here's the one to own, say two experts |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/26/amazon-is-the-name-to-own-in-maga-basket-of-stocks-say-two-experts.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=27 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101054428/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/26/amazon-is-the-name-to-own-in-maga-basket-of-stocks-say-two-experts.html |archivedate=1 January 2020 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Move over FAANG, here comes MAGA - The tech giants are still in rude health |url=https://www.economist.com/business/2018/08/04/the-tech-giants-are-still-in-rude-health |website=The Economist |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Korean website MAGA article\">{{cite web |author1=\uae40\uc81c\ub9bc (Kim Je-rim) |title=\u2018FAANG\u2019 \uc9c0\uace0 \u2018MAGA\u2019 \uc2dc\ub300 \uc628\ub2e4 (\u201cFAANG\u201d is losing and \u201cMAGA\u201d is coming) |url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/economy/view/2019/05/362384/ |website=\ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c |accessdate=27 January 2020 |language=ko |date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Besides [[Saudi Aramco]], which has the highest market cap globally, the GAFAM companies are the next five most valuable public corporations in the world (measured by market capitalisation), as of January 2020.<ref name=\"FXSSI most valuable companies globally, Jan 2020\" /> Nikos Smyrnaios justified the GAFAM grouping as an [[oligopoly]] that appears to take control of the Internet by concentrating market power, financial power and using [[patent]] rights and [[copyright]] within a context of [[capitalism]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> Another grouping, FAANG, replaces Microsoft with [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thestreet.com/story/14320244/1/fang-stocks-index.html |title= FANG Stocks Are Getting Their Own Index |first= Kinsey |last= Grant|publisher= [[TheStreet.com|The Street]] |date= Sep 26, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"fool\">{{cite news |last1=Frankel |first1=Matthew |title=What Are the FANG Stocks? |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2017/09/29/ask-a-fool-what-are-the-fang-stocks.aspx |accessdate=11 August 2018 |work=[[Motley Fool]] |date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAmong the big tech companies, Amazon is a leader in [[e-commerce]]; it is also the leader in providing [[cloud service]]s, with nearly 50% market share. Amazon with 69% market share and Google with 25% market share lead the charge in the area of Artificial Intelligence-based personal digital assistants or [[smart speaker]]s ([[Amazon Echo]] and [[Google Home]]). Apple sells high-margin [[smartphone]]s and other computing devices.<ref name=\"big5\" /><ref>{{Citation|title=How 5 Tech Giants Have Become More Like Governments Than Companies|date=October 26, 2017|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/10/26/560136311/how-5-tech-giants-have-become-more-like-governments-than-companies?t=1558819996409}}</ref> Facebook and Google share a [[digital advertising]] duopoly. In addition to [[social networking]], Facebook also dominates the functions of online [[image sharing]] ([[Instagram]]) and online [[messaging]] ([[WhatsApp]]). Google has monopolized the web-based functions of [[online search]] ([[Google search]]), online [[video sharing]] ([[YouTube]]) and [[online mapping]]-based navigation ([[Google Maps]]). Microsoft continues to dominate in [[Desktop computer|desktop]] [[operating system]] market share ([[Microsoft Windows|Windows]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gs.statcounter.com/os-market-share/desktop/worldwide/#monthly-202001-202001-bar|title=Desktop Operating System Market Share Worldwide, Jan 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=StatCounter GlobalStats|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.is/hNOWZ|archive-date=27 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref> and in office productivity software ([[Microsoft Office]]). Microsoft is also the second biggest company in the [[cloud computing]] industry ([[Microsoft Azure]]),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vargas |first1=Cristina |title=Cloud Market Share 2019: AWS vs Azure vs Google \u2013 Who\u2019s Winning? |url=https://www.skyhighnetworks.com/cloud-security-blog/microsoft-azure-closes-iaas-adoption-gap-with-amazon-aws/ |website=Skyhigh Networks (McAfee) |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref> after Amazon, and is also one of the biggest players in the [[video game]] industry ([[Xbox]]).\n\nFormer Google CEO [[Eric Schmidt]], author [[Phil Simon]], and professor [[Scott Galloway (professor)|Scott Galloway]] have each grouped the GAFA companies together (Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple), on the basis that those companies have driven major [[Social change|societal change]] via their dominance and role in online activities. This is unlike other large tech companies such as [[Microsoft]] and [[IBM]], according to Simon and Galloway.<ref name=\"Simon_redefined\" /><ref name=\"hidden_DNA\" /> In 2011, Eric Schmidt argued that \"Microsoft is not driving the consumer revolution in the minds of the consumers.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Schmidt\u2019s \u201cGang Of Four\u201d Doesn\u2019t Have Room for Microsoft |url=http://allthingsd.com/20110531/eric-schmidts-gang-of-four-doesnt-have-room-for-microsoft/ |website=AllThingsD}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that four characteristics were key in the emergence of GAFA: the theory of [[technological convergence#History of media technological convergence|media and information technology convergence]], [[financialization]], [[deregulation|economic deregulation]] and [[globalization]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> He argued that the promotion of technology convergence by people such as [[Nicholas Negroponte]] made it appear credible and desirable for the Internet to evolve into an oligopoly. Autoregulation and the difficulty of politicians to understand software issues made [[competition law|governmental intervention against monopolies]] ineffective. Financial deregulation led to GAFA's big profit margins (all four except for Amazon had about 20\u201325 percent profit margins in 2014 according to Smyrnaios).\n\n===Globalization===\nAccording to Smyrnaios, globalization has allowed GAFAM to minimize its global taxation load and pay international workers much lower wages than would be required in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n===Oligopoly maintenance===\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that GAFA combines six vertical levels of power, data centers, internet connectivity, computer hardware including [[smartphone]]s, operating systems, Web browsers and other user-level software, and online services. He also discussed horizontal concentration of power, in which diverse services such as email, instant messaging, [[search engine|online searching]], downloading and streaming are combined internally within any of the GAFA members.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n== Antitrust investigations in 2019-2020 ==\n\nIn 2019 and 2020, the Big Tech industry become center of antitrust attention from the [[United States Department of Justice]] and the United States [[Federal Trade Commission]] that included requests to provide information about prior acquisitions and potentially uncompetitive practices. Some Democratic candidates running for president proposed plans to break up Big Tech companies and regulate them as [[utilities]]. \u201cThe role of technology in the economy and in our lives grows more important every day,\u201d said FTC Chairman [[Joe Simons]]. \u201cAs I\u2019ve noted in the past, it makes sense for us to closely examine technology markets to ensure consumers benefit from free and fair competition.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2020/02/ftc-examine-past-acquisitions-large-technology-companies|title=FTC to Examine Past Acquisitions by Large Technology Companies|date=2020-02-11|website=Federal Trade Commission}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2019/02/ftcs-bureau-competition-launches-task-force-monitor-technology|title= FTC\u2019s Bureau of Competition Launches Task Force to Monitor Technology Markets|date=2019-02-26|website=Federal Trade Commission}}</ref>\n\nDiscussions of antitrust policy are clouded, however, by common myths about this widely misunderstood area of the law. The [[Sherman Antitrust Act of 1890]] criminalizes monopolistic business practices, specifically agreements that restraint of trade or commerce. At the same time, the Sherman Act allows organic creation of legitimately successful businesses that gain honest profits from [[consumers]]. The Act\u2019s main function is to preserve a competitive marketplace. The Big Tech companies are large and successful companies, but success alone is not reason enough for antitrust action. A legitimate breach of [[antitrust law]] must be the cause of any action against these giants, otherwise no startup would have an incentive to build the next one. One has to ask how Big Tech companies have gained their dominant market position, because a business is only guilty of monopolization if the monopoly is obtained by means other than providing a better product at a better price. Companies such as [[Google]] must be able to succeed by offering their users a superior experience.\n\nThe correlation between alleged anticompetitive behavior and questionable [[online privacy]] practices is also far from clear. Antitrust law is narrowly tailored to protect consumers from business conduct that harms the competitive process itself. Questionable practices that relate to privacy, however, may require their own regulatory framework of online privacy laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/five-myths/myths-antitrust-law-amazon-google-monopoly/2020/03/20/ead2a072-6a1a-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Five myths about antitrust law|date=2020-03-20|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Opposition==\n[[Scott Galloway (professor)|Scott Galloway]] has criticized the companies for \"avoid[ing] taxes, invad[ing] privacy, and destroy[ing] jobs\",<ref name=\"cnbc_avoid_taxes\" /> while Smyrnaios has described the group as an [[oligopoly]], coming to dominate the online market through [[anti-competitive practices]], ever-increasing financial power, and [[intellectual property law]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> He has argued that the current situation is the result of [[deregulation|economic deregulation]], [[globalization]], and the failure of politicians to understand and respond to developments in technology.\n\nSmyrnaios recommended developing academic analysis of the [[political economy]] of the Internet in order to understand the methods of domination and to criticize these methods in order to encourage opposition to that domination.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n===Use of externally-generated content===\nOn 9 May 2019, the [[Parliament of France]] passed a law intended to force GAFA to pay for [[related rights]] (the reuse of substantial amounts of text, photos or videos), to the publishers and news agencies of the original materials. The law is aimed at implementing [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market#Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive)|Article 15 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]] of the European Union.<ref name=\"leMonde_GAFAM\" />\n\n==BATX and other tech companies==\n{{See also|BATX}}\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that the Asian giant corporations [[Samsung]], [[Alibaba]], [[Baidu]] and [[Tencent]] could or should be included in the definition.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> Together, this has been referred to as \"G-MAFIA + BAT\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/beyond-the-beyond/2019/03/big-nine-g-mafia-bat/ |title=The Big Nine G-MAFIA BAT |last1=Sterling |first1=Bruce |date=15 March 2019 |website=wired.com |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=10 August 2019 |authorlink=Bruce Sterling}}</ref> also including IBM. Samsung is primarily an industrial conglomerate. While a dominant presence in the mobile telephony marketplace, Samsung is presently dependent on the Android ecosystem, which Google controls, hence Samsung is not included in the BAT formulation.\n\n\"BATX\" is also used to refer specifically to the large [[Internet in China|internet companies in China]].<ref name=\"Greven\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/china-watch/technology/new-technology-giants/|title=Meet China\u2019s new tech giants: Alibaba, Baidu, Tencent and Xiaomi|author=Greven, Mark & Wei Wei|date=17 October 2017|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>  \"BATX\" stands for [[Baidu]], [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], [[Tencent]], [[Xiaomi]], the acronym for the four biggest <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ns-businesshub.com/technology/biggest-chinese-tech-companies/|title=Biggest Chinese tech companies: From Alibaba and Huawei to Tencent|date=2019-02-04|website=NS Business|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> tech firms in China. The term BATX is used to refer to the biggest tech giants in China, counter-standing by [[Big Four tech companies|GAFA]] ([[Google]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Facebook]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]])<ref name=\"Chen\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/batx-stocks.asp|title=BATX Stocks|last=Chen|first=James|website=Investopedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> in United States. BATX are few of first tech companies started in the 2000s in the rise of Chinese tech revelution and became widely used among Chinese netizens. Notably, in the recently years after 2015, some other tech companies like [[Huawei]], [[DiDi|DIDI]], [[JD.com|JD]] and [[ByteDance]] have also became some of the up-and-coming biggest tech giants in the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-46480208|title=Why Huawei matters in five charts|last=Hooker|first=Lucy|date=2019-05-20|access-date=2019-10-15|last2=Palumbo|first2=Daniele|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinawhisper.com/top-7-chinese-tech-companies/|title=Top 7 Chinese Tech Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=www.chinawhisper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Aerial view of Apple Park dllu.jpg|Aerial view of Apple Park, the corporate headquarters of Apple Inc., [[Cupertino]], California\nFile:Aerial Microsoft West Campus August 2009.jpg|Microsoft headquarters (western side), [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]], Washington\nFile:Seattle Spheres on May 10, 2018.jpg|Amazon headquarters, [[Seattle]], [[Washington state|Washington]]\nFile:Googleplex HQ.jpg|Alphabet (Google) headquarters, [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]]\nFile:Facebook Campus, Menlo Park, CA.jpg|Facebook headquarters, [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], California\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet|Companies}}\n*[[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)]]\n*[[Big Three (management consultancies)]]\n*[[Big Four accounting firms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"gang4_schmidt\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/05/31/schmidt-gang-four-google-apple-amazon-facebook/|title=Eric Schmidt's Gang Of Four: Google, Apple, Amazon, And Facebook \u2013 TechCrunch|last=Schonfeld|first=Erick|date=31 May 2011|website=techcrunch.com|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/78dN4moDj?url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/05/31/schmidt-gang-four-google-apple-amazon-facebook/ |archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=live|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"cnbc_avoid_taxes\">{{cite web|last1=Pisani|first1=Bob|title=We are letting Amazon and Apple 'avoid taxes, invade privacy, and destroy jobs,' says NYU professor|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/02/scott-galloway-the-four-amazon-apple-google-facebook.html|website=CNBC|date=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Simon_redefined\">{{cite book|url=https://www.philsimon.com/books/the-age-of-the-platform|title=The Age of the Platform: How Amazon, Apple, Facebook, and Google Have Redefined Business|last1=Simon|first1=Phil|date=22 October 2011|publisher=Motion Publishing|year=|isbn=9780982930250|edition=1|location=|pages=312}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hidden_DNA\">{{cite book|title=The Four: The Hidden DNA of Amazon, Apple, Facebook, and Google|last1=Galloway|first=Scott|publisher=Random House|year=2017|isbn=9781473542105|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"leMonde_GAFAM\">{{cite news | last1= Bougon | first1= Fran\u00e7ois | language = fr | title= Face aux Gafam, les d\u00e9put\u00e9s adoptent le droit voisin |trans-title = Members of Parliament pass a related rights law against GAFAM | date= 2019-05-21 | publisher= [[Le Monde]] | url= https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2019/05/10/face-aux-gafam-les-deputes-adoptent-le-droit-voisin_5460399_3234.html |accessdate= 2019-05-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190525235122/https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2019/05/10/face-aux-gafam-les-deputes-adoptent-le-droit-voisin_5460399_3234.html |archivedate= 2019-05-25 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\">{{cite journal | last1 = Smyrnaios | first1 = Nikos | last2 = | first2 = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = L'effet GAFAM : strat\u00e9gies et logiques de l\u2019oligopole de l'internet |trans-title = The GAFAM effect: Strategies and logics of the internet oligopoly |language = fr | journal = [[Communication et langages]] |year=2016 | volume = 188 | issue = | pages = | publisher = [[NecPlus]] | location = | date = | url = https://www.cairn.info/article.php?ID_ARTICLE=COMLA_188_0061# | url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free --> | issn = 0003-5033 | doi = 10.4074/S0336150016012047 | id = | arxiv= | accessdate = 2019-07-13 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190713132708/https://www.cairn.info/article.php?ID_ARTICLE=COMLA_188_0061 | archivedate= 2019-07-13 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ted.com/talks/scott_galloway_how_amazon_apple_facebook_and_google_manipulate_our_emotions How Amazon, Apple, Facebook and Google manipulate our emotions] \u2013 [[Scott Galloway (professor)|Scott Galloway]] at [[TED (conference)|TED]]\n\n[[Category:Technology companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2010s]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Label of large technology companies including Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft}}\n{{expand french|GAFAM|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:10 Largest Corporations by Market Capitalization.png|thumb|400x400px|10 largest corporations by market capitalization]]\nThe term '''\"Big Tech\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/82dff4a4-3283-11e8-ac48-10c6fdc22f03|title=The Economics of Big Tech|date=2018-03-29|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>, along with its synonym '''Tech Giants'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/13/magazine/internet-platform.html|title=We\u2019re Stuck With the Tech Giants. But They\u2019re Stuck With Each Other.|date=2019-11-13|website=New York Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, has been used in [[journalism]] to refer to the largest and most dominant [[Company|companies]] in the [[information technology]] industry.\n\nBy the end of the [[2010s]], five [[United States of America|American]] [[technology company|technology companies]]{{snd}}[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Google]], [[Facebook, Inc.|Facebook]], and [[Microsoft]]{{snd}}were, besides [[Saudi Aramco]], the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|most valuable public companies globally]].<ref name=\"FXSSI most valuable companies globally, Jan 2020\">{{cite web |title=Most Valuable Companies in the World - 2020 |url=https://fxssi.com/top-10-most-valuable-companies-in-the-world |website=FXSSI - Forex Sentiment Board |accessdate=27 January 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/l8mID |archivedate=27 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> At different points, the maximum market capitalization of each of these five technology companies has ranged from around $500 billion to around $1.4 trillion [[United States dollar|USD]]. These companies, specifically Amazon, Apple, Google and Facebook, have been the center of regulatory pressure from the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and [[Federal Trade Commission]] because of concerns over monopolistic practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/2/6/21125026/big-tech-congress-antitrust-investigation-amazon-apple-google-facebook|title=Why Congress\u2019s antitrust investigation should make Big Tech nervous|last=Rey|first=Jason Del|date=2020-02-06|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pymnts.com/antitrust/2019/doj-to-wrap-up-probe-into-facebook-google-amazon-apple-in-2020/|title=DOJ To Wrap Up Probe Into Big Tech In 2020|last=PYMNTS|date=2019-12-11|website=PYMNTS.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/big-tech-s-antitrust-wipeout-33-billion-erased-from-the-value-of-amazon-apple-facebook-and-google-after-doj-announces-probe-1028379566|title=The DOJ's latest probe erased $33 billion from Amazon, Apple, Facebook, and Google {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> There were also two [[China|Chinese]] technology companies in the top ten most valuable publicly traded companies globally at the end of the 2010s, which were [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] and [[Tencent]].\n\nThe biggest American technology companies have replaced the energy giants such as [[Exxon Mobil]], [[BP]], [[Gazprom]], [[PetroChina]] and [[Royal Dutch Shell]] (so-called \"[[Big Oil]]\") from the first decade of the 21st century at the top of the [[NASDAQ]] stock index. They have also outpaced the traditional big media companies such as [[Disney]], [[AT&T]], [[Comcast]] and [[21st Century Fox]] (the so-called \"[[Big Media]]\") by a factor of 10.<ref>{{Citation |title=Tech Giants, Artificial Intelligence, and the Future of Journalism (Open Access) |author=Jason Paul Whittaker |publisher=Routledge |date=Feb 11, 2019 |chapter=Introduction}}</ref> In 2017, the five biggest American IT companies had a combined valuation of over $3.3 trillion, and made up more than 40 percent of the value of the [[Nasdaq 100]].<ref name=\"big5\">{{Citation |title=The 'Big Five' Could Destroy the Tech Ecosystem |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2017-11-15/the-big-five-could-destroy-the-tech-ecosystem}}</ref>\nThere has been speculation that it may not be possible to live day-to-day in the digital world outside of the ecosystem created by the five biggest tech companies (by market capitalisation).<ref>{{Citation |title=It\u2019s almost impossible to function without the big five tech giants |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/feb/17/almost-impossible-to-function-without-big-five-tech-giants}}</ref> Some have also raised the issue of regulating their influence in the areas of privacy, market power, free speech and censorship (including inappropriate content), and national security and law enforcement.<ref>{{Citation |title=Privacy, power and censorship: how to regulate big tech |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/apr/29/big-tech-regulation-facebook-google-amazon}}</ref> On the other hand, by providing cheap or even free services to consumers, they remain popular.<ref name=\"vox\">{{Citation |title=The push to break up Big Tech, explained |first=Matthew |last=Yglesias |authorlink=Matt Yglesias |date=May 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2019/5/3/18520703/big-tech-break-up-explained}}</ref>\n\nOther big technology companies on a global scale include [[Samsung]], [[Intel]], [[IBM]], [[Cisco Systems]], [[Tencent]] and [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]]. Along with Apple, Google, Facebook, and Microsoft, they completed the list of top ten technology companies in the world at the end of 2010s, according to the Forbes Global 2000 list published in 2019, an evaluation based on annual sales, profit, assets, market capitalization, and overall market valuation (Amazon and Alibaba were considered retail companies by Forbes).<ref>{{Citation |title= The Largest Technology Companies In 2019: Apple Reigns As Smartphones Slip And Cloud Services Thrive |author=Jonathan Ponciano |date=May 15, 2019 |publisher= Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonathanponciano/2019/05/15/worlds-largest-tech-companies-2019/#7bac53ea734f}}</ref> \n\n== Membership and definitions ==\nThere have been different definitions and names for the groups of largest companies by different authors. The terms \"Big Four\" and \"Big Five\" are frequently used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/what-are-the-big-four-tech-companies-in-the-us.html|title=What are the Four Big Tech Companies in the US?|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>  One grouping includes Google, Apple, Facebook, and Amazon, which has been called \"GAFA\",<ref name=\"accenture_banking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.accenture.com/us-en/insight-digital-banking-beyond-everyday-bank|title=GAFA Approach to Digital Banking Transformation - Accenture|website=www.accenture.com|language=en}}</ref> the \"Gang of Four\" (after the [[Gang of Four]] political faction in China),<ref name=\"Simon_redefined\" /><ref name=\"gang4_schmidt\" /> and the \"Four Horsemen\" (after the [[Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marketingjournal.org/the-four-horsemen-an-interview-with-scott-galloway/|title=\u201cThe Four Horsemen\u201d \u2013 An Interview with Scott Galloway}}</ref> A more inclusive grouping, GAFAM, defines Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple, and Microsoft as \"Big Tech\" due to their success in the stock market.<ref name=\"Financial Times article on MAGA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c817306c-914e-11e8-b639-7680cedcc421|title=Move over Faangs, make way for Maga|last=Waters|first=Richard|date=27 July 2018|website=Financial Times|access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC article on MAGA\">{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=Pippa |title=Four 'MAGA' stocks are worth a combined $4 trillion. Here's the one to own, say two experts |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/26/amazon-is-the-name-to-own-in-maga-basket-of-stocks-say-two-experts.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=27 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101054428/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/26/amazon-is-the-name-to-own-in-maga-basket-of-stocks-say-two-experts.html |archivedate=1 January 2020 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Move over FAANG, here comes MAGA - The tech giants are still in rude health |url=https://www.economist.com/business/2018/08/04/the-tech-giants-are-still-in-rude-health |website=The Economist |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=4 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Korean website MAGA article\">{{cite web |author1=\uae40\uc81c\ub9bc (Kim Je-rim) |title=\u2018FAANG\u2019 \uc9c0\uace0 \u2018MAGA\u2019 \uc2dc\ub300 \uc628\ub2e4 (\u201cFAANG\u201d is losing and \u201cMAGA\u201d is coming) |url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/economy/view/2019/05/362384/ |website=\ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c |accessdate=27 January 2020 |language=ko |date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Besides [[Saudi Aramco]], which has the highest market cap globally, the GAFAM companies are the next five most valuable public corporations in the world (measured by market capitalisation), as of January 2020.<ref name=\"FXSSI most valuable companies globally, Jan 2020\" /> Nikos Smyrnaios justified the GAFAM grouping as an [[oligopoly]] that appears to take control of the Internet by concentrating market power, financial power and using [[patent]] rights and [[copyright]] within a context of [[capitalism]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> Another grouping, FAANG, replaces Microsoft with [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thestreet.com/story/14320244/1/fang-stocks-index.html |title= FANG Stocks Are Getting Their Own Index |first= Kinsey |last= Grant|publisher= [[TheStreet.com|The Street]] |date= Sep 26, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"fool\">{{cite news |last1=Frankel |first1=Matthew |title=What Are the FANG Stocks? |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2017/09/29/ask-a-fool-what-are-the-fang-stocks.aspx |accessdate=11 August 2018 |work=[[Motley Fool]] |date=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAmong the big tech companies, Amazon is a leader in [[e-commerce]]; it is also the leader in providing [[cloud service]]s, with nearly 50% market share. Amazon with 69% market share and Google with 25% market share lead the charge in the area of Artificial Intelligence-based personal digital assistants or [[smart speaker]]s ([[Amazon Echo]] and [[Google Home]]). Apple sells high-margin [[smartphone]]s and other computing devices.<ref name=\"big5\" /><ref>{{Citation|title=How 5 Tech Giants Have Become More Like Governments Than Companies|date=October 26, 2017|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/10/26/560136311/how-5-tech-giants-have-become-more-like-governments-than-companies?t=1558819996409}}</ref> Facebook and Google share a [[digital advertising]] duopoly. In addition to [[social networking]], Facebook also dominates the functions of online [[image sharing]] ([[Instagram]]) and online [[messaging]] ([[WhatsApp]]). Google has monopolized the web-based functions of [[online search]] ([[Google search]]), online [[video sharing]] ([[YouTube]]) and [[online mapping]]-based navigation ([[Google Maps]]). Microsoft continues to dominate in [[Desktop computer|desktop]] [[operating system]] market share ([[Microsoft Windows|Windows]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gs.statcounter.com/os-market-share/desktop/worldwide/#monthly-202001-202001-bar|title=Desktop Operating System Market Share Worldwide, Jan 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=StatCounter GlobalStats|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.is/hNOWZ|archive-date=27 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref> and in office productivity software ([[Microsoft Office]]). Microsoft is also the second biggest company in the [[cloud computing]] industry ([[Microsoft Azure]]),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vargas |first1=Cristina |title=Cloud Market Share 2019: AWS vs Azure vs Google \u2013 Who\u2019s Winning? |url=https://www.skyhighnetworks.com/cloud-security-blog/microsoft-azure-closes-iaas-adoption-gap-with-amazon-aws/ |website=Skyhigh Networks (McAfee) |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref> after Amazon, and is also one of the biggest players in the [[video game]] industry ([[Xbox]]).\n\nFormer Google CEO [[Eric Schmidt]], author [[Phil Simon]], and professor [[Scott Galloway (professor)|Scott Galloway]] have each grouped the GAFA companies together (Google, Amazon, Facebook, Apple), on the basis that those companies have driven major [[Social change|societal change]] via their dominance and role in online activities. This is unlike other large tech companies such as [[Microsoft]] and [[IBM]], according to Simon and Galloway.<ref name=\"Simon_redefined\" /><ref name=\"hidden_DNA\" /> In 2011, Eric Schmidt argued that \"Microsoft is not driving the consumer revolution in the minds of the consumers.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Schmidt\u2019s \u201cGang Of Four\u201d Doesn\u2019t Have Room for Microsoft |url=http://allthingsd.com/20110531/eric-schmidts-gang-of-four-doesnt-have-room-for-microsoft/ |website=AllThingsD}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that four characteristics were key in the emergence of GAFA: the theory of [[technological convergence#History of media technological convergence|media and information technology convergence]], [[financialization]], [[deregulation|economic deregulation]] and [[globalization]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> He argued that the promotion of technology convergence by people such as [[Nicholas Negroponte]] made it appear credible and desirable for the Internet to evolve into an oligopoly. Autoregulation and the difficulty of politicians to understand software issues made [[competition law|governmental intervention against monopolies]] ineffective. Financial deregulation led to GAFA's big profit margins (all four except for Amazon had about 20\u201325 percent profit margins in 2014 according to Smyrnaios).\n\n===Globalization===\nAccording to Smyrnaios, globalization has allowed GAFAM to minimize its global taxation load and pay international workers much lower wages than would be required in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n===Oligopoly maintenance===\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that GAFA combines six vertical levels of power, data centers, internet connectivity, computer hardware including [[smartphone]]s, operating systems, Web browsers and other user-level software, and online services. He also discussed horizontal concentration of power, in which diverse services such as email, instant messaging, [[search engine|online searching]], downloading and streaming are combined internally within any of the GAFA members.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n== Antitrust investigations in 2019-2020 ==\n\nIn 2019 and 2020, the Big Tech industry become center of antitrust attention from the [[United States Department of Justice]] and the United States [[Federal Trade Commission]] that included requests to provide information about prior acquisitions and potentially uncompetitive practices. Some Democratic candidates running for president proposed plans to break up Big Tech companies and regulate them as [[utilities]]. \u201cThe role of technology in the economy and in our lives grows more important every day,\u201d said FTC Chairman [[Joe Simons]]. \u201cAs I\u2019ve noted in the past, it makes sense for us to closely examine technology markets to ensure consumers benefit from free and fair competition.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2020/02/ftc-examine-past-acquisitions-large-technology-companies|title=FTC to Examine Past Acquisitions by Large Technology Companies|date=2020-02-11|website=Federal Trade Commission}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2019/02/ftcs-bureau-competition-launches-task-force-monitor-technology|title= FTC\u2019s Bureau of Competition Launches Task Force to Monitor Technology Markets|date=2019-02-26|website=Federal Trade Commission}}</ref>\n\nDiscussions of antitrust policy are clouded, however, by common myths about this widely misunderstood area of the law. The [[Sherman Antitrust Act of 1890]] criminalizes monopolistic business practices, specifically agreements that restraint of trade or commerce. At the same time, the Sherman Act allows organic creation of legitimately successful businesses that gain honest profits from [[consumers]]. The Act\u2019s main function is to preserve a competitive marketplace. The Big Tech companies are large and successful companies, but success alone is not reason enough for antitrust action. A legitimate breach of [[antitrust law]] must be the cause of any action against these giants, otherwise no startup would have an incentive to build the next one. One has to ask how Big Tech companies have gained their dominant market position, because a business is only guilty of monopolization if the monopoly is obtained by means other than providing a better product at a better price. Companies such as [[Google]] must be able to succeed by offering their users a superior experience.\n\nThe correlation between alleged anticompetitive behavior and questionable [[online privacy]] practices is also far from clear. Antitrust law is narrowly tailored to protect consumers from business conduct that harms the competitive process itself. Questionable practices that relate to privacy, however, may require their own regulatory framework of online privacy laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/five-myths/myths-antitrust-law-amazon-google-monopoly/2020/03/20/ead2a072-6a1a-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Five myths about antitrust law|date=2020-03-20|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Opposition==\n[[Scott Galloway (professor)|Scott Galloway]] has criticized the companies for \"avoid[ing] taxes, invad[ing] privacy, and destroy[ing] jobs\",<ref name=\"cnbc_avoid_taxes\" /> while Smyrnaios has described the group as an [[oligopoly]], coming to dominate the online market through [[anti-competitive practices]], ever-increasing financial power, and [[intellectual property law]].<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> He has argued that the current situation is the result of [[deregulation|economic deregulation]], [[globalization]], and the failure of politicians to understand and respond to developments in technology.\n\nSmyrnaios recommended developing academic analysis of the [[political economy]] of the Internet in order to understand the methods of domination and to criticize these methods in order to encourage opposition to that domination.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" />\n\n===Use of externally-generated content===\nOn 9 May 2019, the [[Parliament of France]] passed a law intended to force GAFA to pay for [[related rights]] (the reuse of substantial amounts of text, photos or videos), to the publishers and news agencies of the original materials. The law is aimed at implementing [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market#Draft Article 11 (Article 15 of the directive)|Article 15 of the Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]] of the European Union.<ref name=\"leMonde_GAFAM\" />\n\n==BATX and other tech companies==\n{{See also|BATX}}\nSmyrnaios argued in 2016 that the Asian giant corporations [[Samsung]], [[Alibaba]], [[Baidu]] and [[Tencent]] could or should be included in the definition.<ref name=\"Smyrnaios_GAFAM\" /> Together, this has been referred to as \"G-MAFIA + BAT\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/beyond-the-beyond/2019/03/big-nine-g-mafia-bat/ |title=The Big Nine G-MAFIA BAT |last1=Sterling |first1=Bruce |date=15 March 2019 |website=wired.com |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=10 August 2019 |authorlink=Bruce Sterling}}</ref> also including IBM. Samsung is primarily an industrial conglomerate. While a dominant presence in the mobile telephony marketplace, Samsung is presently dependent on the Android ecosystem, which Google controls, hence Samsung is not included in the BAT formulation.\n\n\"BATX\" is also used to refer specifically to the large [[Internet in China|internet companies in China]].<ref name=\"Greven\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/china-watch/technology/new-technology-giants/|title=Meet China\u2019s new tech giants: Alibaba, Baidu, Tencent and Xiaomi|author=Greven, Mark & Wei Wei|date=17 October 2017|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>  \"BATX\" stands for [[Baidu]], [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], [[Tencent]], [[Xiaomi]], the acronym for the four biggest <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ns-businesshub.com/technology/biggest-chinese-tech-companies/|title=Biggest Chinese tech companies: From Alibaba and Huawei to Tencent|date=2019-02-04|website=NS Business|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> tech firms in China. The term BATX is used to refer to the biggest tech giants in China, counter-standing by [[Big Four tech companies|GAFA]] ([[Google]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Facebook]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]])<ref name=\"Chen\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/batx-stocks.asp|title=BATX Stocks|last=Chen|first=James|website=Investopedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> in United States. BATX are few of first tech companies started in the 2000s in the rise of Chinese tech revelution and became widely used among Chinese netizens. Notably, in the recently years after 2015, some other tech companies like [[Huawei]], [[DiDi|DIDI]], [[JD.com|JD]] and [[ByteDance]] have also became some of the up-and-coming biggest tech giants in the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-46480208|title=Why Huawei matters in five charts|last=Hooker|first=Lucy|date=2019-05-20|access-date=2019-10-15|last2=Palumbo|first2=Daniele|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinawhisper.com/top-7-chinese-tech-companies/|title=Top 7 Chinese Tech Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=www.chinawhisper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Aerial view of Apple Park dllu.jpg|Aerial view of Apple Park, the corporate headquarters of Apple Inc., [[Cupertino]], California\nFile:Aerial Microsoft West Campus August 2009.jpg|Microsoft headquarters (western side), [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]], Washington\nFile:Seattle Spheres on May 10, 2018.jpg|Amazon headquarters, [[Seattle]], [[Washington state|Washington]]\nFile:Googleplex HQ.jpg|Alphabet (Google) headquarters, [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]]\nFile:Facebook Campus, Menlo Park, CA.jpg|Facebook headquarters, [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], California\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet|Companies}}\n*[[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)]]\n*[[Big Three (management consultancies)]]\n*[[Big Four accounting firms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"gang4_schmidt\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/05/31/schmidt-gang-four-google-apple-amazon-facebook/|title=Eric Schmidt's Gang Of Four: Google, Apple, Amazon, And Facebook \u2013 TechCrunch|last=Schonfeld|first=Erick|date=31 May 2011|website=techcrunch.com|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/78dN4moDj?url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/05/31/schmidt-gang-four-google-apple-amazon-facebook/ |archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=live|access-date=2019-05-25}}</